{"title_page": "Kaymak", "text_new": "{{short description|creamy dairy product similar to clotted cream}}\n{{About|a creamy dairy product|the surname|Kaymak (surname)}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Kaymak\n| image            = Kaymak in Turkey.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Kaymak from [[Turkish cuisine|Turkey]]\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Turkic [[Central Asia]]\n| region           = [[Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey]], [[Greece]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Breakfast]] and [[dessert]]\n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]]\n| variations       = Kaymar, Gaymar, Qaimar, Qaimaq\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Kaymak''' is a creamy [[dairy product]] similar to [[clotted cream]], made from the [[milk]] of [[water buffalo]], [[cow]]s, [[sheep]], or [[goat]]s in [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asia]], some [[Balkan cuisine|Balkan]] countries, some [[Caucasus]] countries, [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] regions, [[Iranian cuisine|Iran]], [[Iraq]] and [[Afghan cuisine|Afghanistan]].\n\nThe traditional method of making kaymak is to boil the milk slowly, then simmer it for two hours over a very low heat. After the heat source is shut off, the cream is skimmed and left to chill (and mildly [[fermentation (food)|ferment]]) for several hours or days. Kaymak has a high percentage of [[milk fat]], typically about 60%. It has a thick, creamy consistency (not entirely compact, because of milk protein fibers) and a rich taste.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word kaymak has [[Central Asia]]n [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] origins, possibly formed from the verb kaymak, which means melt and molding of metal in [[Turkic languages|Turkic]].<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kaymak|title=kaymak|publisher=Ni\u015fanyanS\u00f6zl\u00fck|language=Turkish|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref> The first written records of the word kaymak is in the well-known book of [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], ''[[D\u012bw\u0101n Lugh\u0101t al-Turk]]''. The word remains as ''kaylgmak'' in Mongolian, and with small variations in Turkic languages as ''qaymaq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], ''qaymoq'' in [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], \u049b\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u049b in [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]] and [[Shor language|Shor]], \u043a\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u043a in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], ''kaymak'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]]<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\"/>, ga\u00fdmak in [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 (''kaimaghi'') in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], and \u03ba\u03b1\u03ca\u03bc\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 (''ka\u00efm\u00e1ki'') in [[Greek language|Greek]].\n\n==Turkey==\nShops in [[Turkey]] have been devoted to kaymak production and consumption for centuries. Kaymak is mainly consumed today for breakfast along with the traditional [[Turkish breakfast]]. One type of kaymak is found in the [[Afyonkarahisar]] region where the water buffalo are fed from the residue of poppy seeds pressed for oil. Kaymak can also describe the creamy foam in the traditional \"black\" Turkish coffee. Kaymak is traditionally eaten with [[baklava]] and other [[Turkish desserts]], fruit preserve and honey or as a filling in [[pancake]]s.\n\n==Balkans==\n[[File:Cicvara (10274863185).jpg|thumb|''Palenta'', cornmeal mush with kajmak and [[\u010dvarci]]]]\n[[File:Traditional wooden bowls for making kaymak.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Traditional wooden bowls for making and storing kaymak ([[Ethnographic Museum, Belgrade]])]]\nKnown as ''kajmak'', it is almost always made at home, though there is beginning to be commercial production. Kajmak is most expensive when freshest&mdash;only a day or two old. It can keep for weeks in the fridge but becomes harder and loses quality.<ref name=NIN>{{cite news |title=Sve srpske ka\u0161ike |first=Nikola|last=Vrzi\u0107 |url=http://www.nin.co.rs/2000-12/28/15928.html |work=[[NIN (magazine)|NIN]] |date=December 28, 2000 |accessdate=13 June 2012 |language=Serbian |format=Windows-1250}}</ref> Kajmak can also be matured in dried animal skin sacks; variation is called ''skorup''. ''Kajmak'' also describes the creamy foam in the Turkish coffee.\n\nIt is usually enjoyed as an [[appetizer]] or for Saturday morning breakfast, as Saturdays are market days with the best kajmak, but also as a [[condiment]]. The simplest recipe is ''lepinja sa kajmakom'' ([[bun]] [[bread]] filled with kaymak in Serbia) consumed for breakfast or as [[fast food]]. [[Bosnians]], [[Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]], and [[North Macedonia|Macedonians]] consider it a national meal. Other traditional dishes with kajmak (sold in restaurants) include ''[[pljeskavica]] sa kajmakom'' (the [[Balkans|Balkan]] version of a hamburger patty topped with melted kajmak), as well as ''ribi\u0107 u kajmaku'' (beef shank, simmered with kajmak).\n\n==Iraq==\n[[File:Iraqi-Gaimar-Kaymak.jpg|thumbnail|150px|Iraqi Gaimar made from [[water buffalo]] milk]]\nIn [[Iraq]], it is called gaimar, geymar or qaimar and is very popular. Iraqi gaimar is usually made from the rich, fatty milk of water buffaloes, which are prevalent in the marshes of Southern Iraq.\n\nIt is available both factory-produced and from local vendors (farmers) commonly known as Arab, Arbans or [[Madan (people)|Madan]], and so is sometimes referred to as ''gaimar Arab'', ''gaimar maadan'', or farmer's ''gaimar''.\n\nIraqis like to serve Gaimar for breakfast with fresh bread, honey or jam.  However, the most popular way is to spread it on a type of Iraqi pastry bread called \"Kahi\", smother it with [[date honey]] and then wash it down with hot tea.  Gaimar on kahi with date syrup is a long-standing traditional breakfast all over Baghdad and throughout the whole of Southern Iraq.\n\n==Iran==\nIn [[Iran]], ''sarsheer'' (\u0633\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u0631) is used to describe a different method which does not involve heating the milk, thus keeping enzymes and other cultures of the milk alive. The word ''kaymak'' (''qaymaq'') is also used for the boiled method. ''Qaymaq'' is a Turkish word used to describe this product among the Azari people of Iran.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''Qaimak'' or qaymaq has a thinner quality and is eaten for breakfast meals usually with bread. People typically top qaimak with honey, sugar, or mix it with jam. It can be spread on pastries or even added to milk tea. Qaimak can be purchased at grocery stores in Afghanistan or made at home. It is quite a long process to make at home, involving hours stirring the milk pot. Qaimak can be found at Afghan/Iranian grocery stores in the west, but is not as rich as homemade. While a lot qaimak variations are made from buffaloes' milk, Afghan qaimak can be made from cows' milk.\n\n==Georgia==\n[[File:Kaimaghi.jpg|thumb|A bucket containing kaimaghi in a home in Keda, Georgia.]]\nIn the [[Adjara]] region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], bordering Turkey, \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 or ''kaimaghi'' is made from cow's milk in homes in the mountainous municipalities of [[Keda, Georgia|Keda]], [[Shuakhevi]], and [[Khulo]]. It is typically eaten with [[Georgian cheese]] and/or bread, and is only rarely served in restaurants.\n\n==Greece==\n''Kaimaki'' in [[Greece]] refers to [[mastic (plant resin)|mastic]]-flavored ice cream that is widely available and often served alongside traditional desserts.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Malai]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928145321/http://editore.slowfood.com/editore/riviste/slowark/EN/25/papavero.html The Poppy Growers of \u0130smailk\u00f6y (2002)]\n* Davidson, Alan. Oxford Companion to Food (1999). \"Kaymak\", pp.&nbsp;428\u2013429. {{ISBN|0-19-211579-0}}\n* [http://www.travelserbia.info/serbian-cuisine.php An Introduction into the Serbian Cuisine]\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624222707/http://www.havuzsauna.com/detay.asp?y=639 The famous kaymak breakfast of \"Pando Usta\" at Be\u015fikta\u015f, Istanbul]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060926222537/http://faq.macedonia.org/cuisine/kajmak.html Kaymak recipe]\n\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Cuisine of Serbia}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{List of intangible cultural heritage of Serbia}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Appetizers]]\n[[Category:Balkan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Condiments]]\n[[Category:Fermented dairy products]]\n[[Category:Iranian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Kyrgyz cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|creamy dairy product similar to clotted cream}}\n{{About|a creamy dairy product|the surname|Kaymak (surname)}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Kaymak\n| image            = Kaymak in Turkey.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Kaymak from [[Turkish cuisine|Turkey]]\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Turkic [[Central Asia]]\n| region           = [[Azerbaijan]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey]], [[Greece]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Breakfast]] and [[dessert]]\n| type             = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]]\n| variations       = Kaymar, Gaymar, Qaimar, Qaimaq\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Kaymak''' is a creamy [[dairy product]] similar to [[clotted cream]], made from the [[milk]] of [[water buffalo]], [[cow]]s, [[sheep]], or [[goat]]s in [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asia]], some [[Balkan cuisine|Balkan]] countries, some [[Caucasus]] countries, [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] regions, [[Iranian cuisine|Iran]], [[Iraq]] and [[Afghan cuisine|Afghanistan]].\n\nThe traditional method of making kaymak is to boil the milk slowly, then simmer it for two hours over a very low heat. After the heat source is shut off, the cream is skimmed and left to chill (and mildly [[fermentation (food)|ferment]]) for several hours or days. Kaymak has a high percentage of [[milk fat]], typically about 60%. It has a thick, creamy consistency (not entirely compact, because of milk protein fibers) and a rich taste.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word kaymak has [[Central Asia]]n [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] origins, possibly formed from the verb kaymak, which means melt and molding of metal in [[Turkic languages|Turkic]].<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kaymak|title=kaymak|publisher=Ni\u015fanyanS\u00f6zl\u00fck|language=Turkish|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref> The first written records of the word kaymak is in the well-known book of [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], ''[[D\u012bw\u0101n Lugh\u0101t al-Turk]]''. The word remains as ''kaylgmak'' in Mongolian, and with small variations in Turkic languages as ''qaymaq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], ''qaymoq'' in [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]], \u049b\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u049b in [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]] and [[Shor language|Shor]], \u043a\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0430\u043a in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], ''kaymak'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]]<ref name=\"nisanyansozluk.com\"/>, ga\u00fdmak in [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 (''kaimaghi'') in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], and \u03ba\u03b1\u03ca\u03bc\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 (''ka\u00efm\u00e1ki'') in [[Greek language|Greek]].\n\n==Turkey==\nShops in [[Turkey]] have been devoted to kaymak production and consumption for centuries. Kaymak is mainly consumed today for breakfast along with the traditional [[Turkish breakfast]]. One type of kaymak is found in the [[Afyonkarahisar]] region where the water buffalo are fed from the residue of poppy seeds pressed for oil. Kaymak can also describe the creamy foam in the traditional \"black\" Turkish coffee. Kaymak is traditionally eaten with [[baklava]] and other [[Turkish desserts]], fruit preserve and honey or as a filling in [[pancake]]s.\n\n==Balkans==\n[[File:Cicvara (10274863185).jpg|thumb|''Palenta'', cornmeal mush with kajmak and [[\u010dvarci]]]]\n[[File:Traditional wooden bowls for making kaymak.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Traditional wooden bowls for making and storing kaymak ([[Ethnographic Museum, Belgrade]])]]\nKnown as ''kajmak'', it is almost always made at home, though there is beginning to be commercial production. Kajmak is most expensive when freshest&mdash;only a day or two old. It can keep for weeks in the fridge but becomes harder and loses quality.<ref name=NIN>{{cite news |title=Sve srpske ka\u0161ike |first=Nikola|last=Vrzi\u0107 |url=http://www.nin.co.rs/2000-12/28/15928.html |work=[[NIN (magazine)|NIN]] |date=December 28, 2000 |accessdate=13 June 2012 |language=Serbian |format=Windows-1250}}</ref> Kajmak can also be matured in dried animal skin sacks; variation is called ''skorup''. ''Kajmak'' also describes the creamy foam in the Turkish coffee.\n\nIt is usually enjoyed as an [[appetizer]] or for Saturday morning breakfast, as Saturdays are market days with the best kajmak, but also as a [[condiment]]. The simplest recipe is ''lepinja sa kajmakom'' ([[bun]] [[bread]] filled with kaymak in Serbia) consumed for breakfast or as [[fast food]]. [[Bosnians]], [[Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]], and [[North Macedonia|Macedonians]] consider it a national meal. Other traditional dishes with kajmak (sold in restaurants) include ''[[pljeskavica]] sa kajmakom'' (the [[Balkans|Balkan]] version of a hamburger patty topped with melted kajmak), as well as ''ribi\u0107 u kajmaku'' (beef shank, simmered with kajmak).\n\n==Iraq==\n[[File:Iraqi-Gaimar-Kaymak.jpg|thumbnail|150px|Iraqi Gaimar made from [[water buffalo]] milk]]\nIn [[Iraq]], it is called gaimar, geymar or qaimar and is very popular. Iraqi gaimar is usually made from the rich, fatty milk of water buffaloes, which are prevalent in the marshes of Southern Iraq.\n\nIt is available both factory-produced and from local vendors (farmers) commonly known as Arab, Arbans or [[Madan (people)|Madan]], and so is sometimes referred to as ''gaimar Arab'', ''gaimar maadan'', or farmer's ''gaimar''.\n\nIraqis like to serve Gaimar for breakfast with fresh bread, honey or jam.  However, the most popular way is to spread it on a type of Iraqi pastry bread called \"Kahi\", smother it with [[date honey]] and then wash it down with hot tea.  Gaimar on kahi with date syrup is a long-standing traditional breakfast all over Baghdad and throughout the whole of Southern Iraq.\n\n==Iran==\nIn [[Iran]], ''sarsheer'' (\u0633\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u0631) is used to describe a different method which does not involve heating the milk, thus keeping enzymes and other cultures of the milk alive. The word ''kaymak'' (''qaymaq'') is also used for the boiled method. ''Qaymaq'' is a Turkish word used to describe this product among the Azari people of Iran.\n\n==Afghanistan==\nIn [[Afghanistan]], ''Qaimak'' or qaymaq has a thinner quality and is eaten for breakfast meals usually with bread. People typically top qaimak with honey, sugar, or mix it with jam. It can be spread on pastries or even added to milk tea. Qaimak can be purchased at grocery stores in Afghanistan or made at home. It is quite a long process to make at home, involving hours of stirring the milk pot. Qaimak can be found at Afghan/Iranian grocery stores in the west, packaged qaimak is not as rich as homemade. While a lot qaimak variations are made from buffalo milk, Afghan qaimak can be made from cows' milk.\n\n==Georgia==\n[[File:Kaimaghi.jpg|thumb|A bucket containing kaimaghi in a home in Keda, Georgia.]]\nIn the [[Adjara]] region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], bordering Turkey, \u10d9\u10d0\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e6\u10d8 or ''kaimaghi'' is made from cow's milk in homes in the mountainous municipalities of [[Keda, Georgia|Keda]], [[Shuakhevi]], and [[Khulo]]. It is typically eaten with [[Georgian cheese]] and/or bread, and is only rarely served in restaurants.\n\n==Greece==\n''Kaimaki'' in [[Greece]] refers to [[mastic (plant resin)|mastic]]-flavored ice cream that is widely available and often served alongside traditional desserts.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Malai]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928145321/http://editore.slowfood.com/editore/riviste/slowark/EN/25/papavero.html The Poppy Growers of \u0130smailk\u00f6y (2002)]\n* Davidson, Alan. Oxford Companion to Food (1999). \"Kaymak\", pp.&nbsp;428\u2013429. {{ISBN|0-19-211579-0}}\n* [http://www.travelserbia.info/serbian-cuisine.php An Introduction into the Serbian Cuisine]\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624222707/http://www.havuzsauna.com/detay.asp?y=639 The famous kaymak breakfast of \"Pando Usta\" at Be\u015fikta\u015f, Istanbul]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060926222537/http://faq.macedonia.org/cuisine/kajmak.html Kaymak recipe]\n\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Condiments}}\n{{Cuisine of Serbia}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{List of intangible cultural heritage of Serbia}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Appetizers]]\n[[Category:Balkan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Condiments]]\n[[Category:Fermented dairy products]]\n[[Category:Iranian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Kyrgyz cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "Mucketymuck", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfghanistan", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaymak"}
{"title_page": "Hormisdas Djibri", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name=Hormisdas Etienne Jabri (Estefan Jabri) \n|image=\n|church=[[Chaldean Catholic Church]]\n|bishop_of=Bishop of [[Kirkuk (Chaldean Archdiocese)|Kirkuk]]\n|appointed=31 August 1917\n|ended=18 July 1953\n|birth_date=8 January 1872\n|birth_place=[[Mosul]]\n|death_date=18 July 1953\n|predecessor=Theodore Massaieh\n|successor=Raphael Rabban\n|ordination= 4 June 1893 ([[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|Priest]])\n|consecration = 30 Nov 1902 ([[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Bishop]])\n|consecrated_by=[[Yousef VI Emmanuel II Thomas|Yousef VI Thomas]]\n}}\n\n'''Hormisdas Etienne Djibri''' [or ''Stephen Jibri (Mutran Estefan Jabri)]'', 1872\u20131953) was Archbishop of [[Kirkuk (Chaldean Archdiocese)|Kirkuk]], Sulaimaniya and Arbil of the [[Chaldean Catholic Church]] from 1917 until his death in 1953. Making him the longest serving archbishop of the Chaldean church with 46 years of service.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fiey | first =Jean Maurice | title = Puor un Oriens Christianus Novus, Repertoire des dioceses syriaques orientaux et occidentaux: | publisher = Steiner | location = Beirut | year = 1993 | isbn = 3-515-05718-8 |page=64 }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHormisdas Etienne Djibri (Mutran Estefan Jabri) was born in [[Mosul]] on 8 January 1872.  He was ordained a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]] on 4 June 1893. He was appointed [[auxiliary bishop]] of Kirkuk and consecrated [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] on 30 Nov 1902 by Patriarch [[Yousef VI Emmanuel II Thomas]].<ref name=\"CH\">{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bdji|Archbishop Hormisdas Etienne Djibri|23 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 1917, Archbishop Estefan Jabri succeeded Theodore Massaieh as Archbishop of Kirkuk. Following the first world war, he found refuge for those displaced by the conflict by leading them to the city of Ninevah (Mosul) and the northern Christian villages of Iraq, including Inkawa and Alqosh. He built the Church of Saint Joseph of Kirkuk, the Church of Saint Georgis of Inkawa, the Arbil Chaldean church and the church of Saint Mary in Shaklawa. He refurbished many of existing Chaldean churches as well as preserving the heritage of monasteries, including [[Rabban Hormizd Monastery|Rabban Hormiz]]. He died on 18 July 1953.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djibri, Hormisdas}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chaldean bishops]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name=Hormisdas Etienne Jabri (Estefan Jabri) \n|image=\n|church=[[Chaldean Catholic Church]]\n|bishop_of=Bishop of [[Kirkuk (Chaldean Archdiocese)|Kirkuk]]\n|appointed=31 August 1917\n|ended=18 July 1953\n|birth_date=8 January 1872\n|birth_place=[[Mosul]]\n|death_date=18 July 1953\n|predecessor=Theodore Massaieh\n|successor=Raphael Rabban\n|ordination= 4 June 1893 ([[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|Priest]])\n|consecration = 30 Nov 1902 ([[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Bishop]])\n|consecrated_by=[[Yousef VI Emmanuel II Thomas|Yousef VI Thomas]]\n}}\n\n'''Hormisdas Etienne Djibri''' [or ''Stephen Jibri (Mutran Estefan Jabri)]'', 1872\u20131953) was Archbishop of [[Kirkuk (Chaldean Archdiocese)|Kirkuk]], Sulaimaniya and Arbil of the [[Chaldean Catholic Church]] from 1917 until his death in 1953. Making him the longest serving archbishop of the Chaldean church with 46 years of service.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fiey | first =Jean Maurice | title = Puor un Oriens Christianus Novus, Repertoire des dioceses syriaques orientaux et occidentaux: | publisher = Steiner | location = Beirut | year = 1993 | isbn = 3-515-05718-8 |page=64 }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHormisdas Etienne Djibri (Mutran Estefan Jabri) was born in [[Mosul]] on 8 January 1872.  He was ordained a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]] on 4 June 1893. He was appointed [[auxiliary bishop]] of Kirkuk and consecrated [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] on 30 Nov 1902 by Patriarch [[Yousef VI Emmanuel II Thomas]].<ref name=\"CH\">{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bdji|Archbishop Hormisdas Etienne Djibri|23 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 1917, ArchBishop Estefan Jabri succeeded Theodore Massaieh as Archbishop of Kirkuk. Following the first world war, he found refuge for those displaced by the conflict by leading them to the city of Ninevah (Mosul) and the northern Christian villages of Iraq, including Inkawa and Alqosh. He built the Church of Saint Joseph of Kirkuk, the Church of Saint Georgis of Inkawa, the Arbil Chaldean church and the church of Saint Mary in Shaklawa. He refurbished many of existing Chaldean churches as well as preserving the heritage of monasteries, including [[Rabban Hormizd Monastery|Rabban Hormiz]]. He died on 18 July 1953.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djibri, Hormisdas}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chaldean bishops]]\n", "name_user": "Dcheney", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:fix ArchBishop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormisdas_Djibri"}
{"title_page": "Confluence Tower", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n|name=Confluence Tower\n|alternate_names= Lewis and Clark Confluence Tower\n|image=Confluence Tower.jpg\n|caption=The Confluence Tower in May 2013\n|coordinates = {{coord|38.8109|-90.1007|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|altitude=\n|building_type=\n|architectural_style=\n|structural_system=\n|cost=\n|location=435 Confluence Tower Drive, [[Hartford, Illinois|Hartford]], [[Illinois]], {{Flag|United States}}\n|start_date=\n|completion_date=\n|inauguration_date=\n|height={{convert|180|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|width=\n|main_contractor=\n|architect=\n|architecture_firm=\n|structural_engineer=\n}}\n\nThe '''Lewis and Clark Confluence Tower''' is a {{convert|180|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} tower on the [[Illinois]] bank of the [[Mississippi River]] at the [[confluence]] of it and the [[Missouri River]]. The tower complements the [[Lewis and Clark State Historic Site]], about one mile to the south, where the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] made winter camp before setting up the Missouri river.<ref name=CST>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/lifestyles/travel/2274676,lewis-clark-tower-hartford-st-louis-051610.article|title=New Illinois tower has things looking up Downstate|last=Suhr|first=Jim|date=May 16, 2010|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=1 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe tower has platforms at 50, 100, and 150 feet, providing a good view of the confluence of the Missouri and Mississippi Rivers. Downtown [[St. Louis]] and the [[Gateway Arch]] can also be seen from the tower.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stlbeacon.org/content/view/102696/341/ |title=Lewis and Clark tower gives bird's eye view of the Confluence |last=Leonard |first=Mary Delach |date=May 27, 2010 |publisher=[[St. Louis Beacon]] |accessdate=1 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601134049/http://www.stlbeacon.org/content/view/102696/341/ |archivedate=1 June 2010 }}</ref> The tower contains two legs joined by viewing platforms, with an elevator in one leg and stairs in the other.<ref name=CST /> Its construction, lasting from 2002 to 2010, was funded by $5 million from local and state sources.<ref name=CST />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.confluencetower.com/ Confluence Tower] &mdash; official website\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2v7tVBqH9ZA Confluence Tower on KETC] &mdash; local public television station [[KETC]] profiles the tower\n\n[[Category:Towers in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Mississippi River]]\n[[Category:Missouri River]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Madison County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 2010]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Madison County, Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n|name=Confluence Tower\n|alternate_names= Lewis and Clark Confluence Tower\n|image=Confluence Tower.jpg\n|caption=The Confluence Tower in May 2013\n|coordinates = {{coord|38.8109|-90.1007|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|altitude=\n|building_type=\n|architectural_style=\n|structural_system=\n|cost=\n|location=435 Confluence Tower Drive, [[Hartford, Illinois|Hartford]], [[Illinois]], {{Flag|United States}}\n|start_date=\n|completion_date=\n|inauguration_date=\n|height={{convert|180|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|width=\n|main_contractor=\n|architect=\n|architecture_firm=\n|structural_engineer=\n}}\n\nThe '''Lewis and Clark Confluence Tower''' is a {{convert|180|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} tower on the [[Illinois]] bank of the [[Mississippi River]] at the [[confluence]] of it and the [[Missouri River]]. The tower complements the [[Lewis and Clark State Historic Site]], about one mile to the south, where the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] made winter camp before setting up the Missouri river.<ref name=CST>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/lifestyles/travel/2274676,lewis-clark-tower-hartford-st-louis-051610.article|title=New Illinois tower has things looking up Downstate|last=Suhr|first=Jim|date=May 16, 2010|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=1 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe tower has platforms at 50, 100, and 150 feet, providing a good view of the confluence of the Missouri and Mississippi Rivers. Downtown [[St. Louis]] and the [[Gateway Arch]] can also be seen from the tower.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stlbeacon.org/content/view/102696/341/ |title=Lewis and Clark tower gives bird's eye view of the Confluence |last=Leonard |first=Mary Delach |date=May 27, 2010 |publisher=[[St. Louis Beacon]] |accessdate=1 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601134049/http://www.stlbeacon.org/content/view/102696/341/ |archivedate=1 June 2010 }}</ref> The tower contains two legs joined by viewing platforms, with an elevator in one leg and stairs in the other.<ref name=CST /> Its construction, lasting from 2002 to 2010, was funded by $5 million from local and state sources.<ref name=CST />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.confluencetower.com/ Confluence Tower] &mdash; official website\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2v7tVBqH9ZA Confluence Tower on KETC] &mdash; local public television station [[KETC]] profiles the tower\n\n[[Category:Towers in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Mississippi River]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Missouri River]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Madison County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 2010]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Madison County, Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confluence_Tower"}
{"title_page": "Peach Belt Conference", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n|name = Peach Belt Conference\n|short_name = PBC\n|established = 1990\n|dissolved = \n|logo = Peach Belt Conference logo.svg\n|logo_size = 150\n|association = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]\n|division = [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]\n|subdivision = \n|members = 12\n|sports = 15\n|mens = 7\n|womens = 8\n|region = [[Southeastern United States]]\n|former_names = \n|hq_city = Augusta\n|hq_state = Georgia\n|commissioner = David Brunk\n|since = 2007\n|website = [http://www.peachbeltconference.org peachbeltconference.org]\n|color = \n|font_color = \n|map = Peachbeltstates.png\n|map_size = 250\n}}\n\nThe '''Peach Belt Conference''' ('''PBC''') is a collegiate [[List of NCAA conferences|athletic conference]] affiliated with the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA)'s [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] level.  The twelve member institutions are located in the [[South Atlantic states]] of [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]], and [[Florida]].  In addition, there are five affiliate members who participate in one sport each; where their home conference does not sponsor that sport.\n\nSince its inception in 1990-91, the Peach Belt has, across all sanctioned sports, produced 30 national champions and additional 27 national finalists. Starting with only two championships in 1991, in men's and women's basketball, the conference has expanded to 13 championship sports with the addition of women's golf in the fall of 2009.\n\n==History==\n\nThe conference traces its roots back to November 1988 when 11 schools first met in Greenville, S.C. to form a Division II conference. Following a second meeting on Dec. 3, 1989, five of those 11 schools, plus two others, formed the Peach Belt Athletic Conference and began play in the fall of 1990.\n\nThe seven charter members of the conference were [[Armstrong State University|Armstrong Atlantic State University]] (now Armstrong State University), [[Columbus State University]], [[Francis Marion University]], [[Georgia College & State University|Georgia College]] (now Georgia College & State University), [[Lander University]], [[University of South Carolina Aiken|USC Aiken]], and [[University of South Carolina Upstate|USC Upstate]]. The name Peach Belt Athletic Conference was adopted in January 1990 and modified to Peach Belt Conference in May 2000.\n\n[[Augusta State University]] joined the conference in 1991 and [[University of North Carolina at Pembroke|UNC Pembroke]] became the ninth member on July 1, 1992. They were followed by [[Kennesaw State University]] on July 1, 1994, [[Clayton State University]] on July 1, 1995 and the [[University of North Florida]] on July 1, 1997. Kennesaw State and North Florida departed for the Division I ranks in 2005, USC Upstate did the same in 2007, and the conference welcomed in [[North Georgia College & State University]] in 2005 and [[Georgia Southwestern State University]] in 2006. In 2009-10, the [[University of Montevallo]] and [[Flagler College]] were added, returning a league presence to Florida and broke new ground in Alabama. In 2012-13, the Peach Belt expanded to 14 members, the most the league has ever had, with the addition of [[Young Harris College]]. On January 8, 2013, the [[University System of Georgia]] finalized the mergers of two conference members into new institutions. Augusta State was merged into Georgia Regents University, which was renamed in 2015 as [[Augusta University]], and NGCSU was merged into the [[University of North Georgia]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Board of Regents finalizes consolidations, approves presidents|url=http://www.usg.edu/news/release/board_of_regents_finalizes_consolidations_appoints_presidents |publisher=University System of Georgia|accessdate=2013-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/local-education/so-long-georgia-regents-hello-augusta-university/nnfgk/|title=So long, Georgia Regents. Hello, Augusta University|publisher=}}</ref> In both cases, the new institutions inherited the Peach Belt memberships of the older schools.\n\n[[File:Peach Belt Conference membership (as of 2014).png|thumb|Map of Southeastern United States with member institutions in the Division II Peach Belt Conference]]\nThe Peach Belt was less than a year old before capturing its first of many national championships. The Columbus State golf team took the honor by winning the 1992 national crown, the first of three golf championships the Cougars own. One year later, the Lander men's tennis team began their record-breaking run of eight straight national titles, the first PBC dynasty. Since then, USCA men's golf has won three straight national titles from 2004-06 while AASU women's tennis has captured four titles overall.\n\nThe 2010-11 season was one of the most memorable the league has ever had. Clayton State became the first PBC women's basketball team to capture a national championship. Montevallo watched their men's basketball team reach the Elite Eight, eventually competing in the National Championship Game. Unfortunately, their run came to an end with a loss to [[Western Washington University]]. The Columbus State men's tennis team reached the national semifinals while the Clayton State and Armstrong Atlantic State women's tennis teams also played in the national semifinals. The North Georgia softball team made an unprecedented third straight appearance in the NCAA Women's College World Series, while Columbus State's Meshack Koyiaki registered a runner-up finish at the Men's Cross Country National Championships. In all, 46 Peach Belt teams made appearances in the NCAA postseason, including seven men's tennis teams and six each in the sports of men's golf and women's tennis.\n\nDavid Brunk was named the second PBC commissioner in May 2007. Brunk replaced Marvin Vanover, who was the first PBC commissioner from 1991 to 2007. Brunk is charged with continuing the strong growth of the conference as its second era begins.\n\nDr. Kendall Blanchard, president of Georgia Southwestern State University, began the second of his two-year term as the league president in July 2011.\n\nIn April, 2020, Francis Marion University and the University of North Carolina at Pembroke announced that they are leaving the Peach Belt Conference effective 2021-22, and will both join [[Conference Carolinas]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Conference Carolinas Announces Addition of Francis Marion and UNC Pembroke|url=https://www.conferencecarolinas.com/newmembers |publisher=Conference Carolinas|accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe conference currently holds championships in 13 sports, six for men and seven for women. They are men's and women's cross country, men's and women's soccer, volleyball, men's and women's basketball, men's and women's tennis, baseball, softball and men's and women's golf.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peachbeltconference.org/information/about/history|title=Peach Belt Conference History|publisher=Peach Belt Conference|accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Member schools==\n\n===Current members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colors\n!Joined\n|-\n![[Augusta University]]\n|[[Augusta, Georgia]]\n|1828\n|[[Public university|Public]]\n|9,000\n|[[Augusta Jaguars|Jaguars]]\n|{{college color boxes|Augusta Jaguars}}\n|1991\n|-\n![[Clayton State University]]\n|[[Morrow, Georgia]]\n|1969\n|Public\n|7,145\n|[[Clayton State Lakers|Lakers]]\n|{{college color boxes|Clayton State Lakers}}\n|1995\n|-\n![[Columbus State University]]\n|[[Columbus, Georgia]]\n|1958\n|Public\n|8,597\n|[[Columbus State Cougars|Cougars]]\n|{{college color boxes|Columbus State Cougars}}\n|1990\n|-\n![[Flagler College]]\n|{{sort|Saint Augustine|[[St. Augustine, Florida]]}}\n|1968\n|[[Private university|Private]] ([[Nonsectarian]])\n|2,046\n|[[Flagler Saints|Saints]]\n|{{college color boxes|Flagler Saints}}\n|2009\n|-\n![[Francis Marion University]]\n|[[Florence, South Carolina]]\n|1970\n|Public\n|4,187\n|[[Francis Marion Patriots|Patriots]]\n|{{college color boxes|Francis Marion Patriots}}\n|1990\n|-\n![[Georgia College & State University]]\n|[[Milledgeville, Georgia]]\n|1889\n|Public\n|6,041\n|[[Georgia College Bobcats|Bobcats]]\n|{{college color boxes|Georgia College Bobcats}}\n|1990\n|-\n![[Georgia Southwestern State University]]\n|[[Americus, Georgia]]\n|1906\n|Public\n|3,033\n|[[Georgia Southwestern State Hurricanes|Hurricanes]]\n|{{college color boxes|Georgia Southwestern State Hurricanes}}\n|2006\n|-\n![[Lander University]]\n|[[Greenwood, South Carolina]]\n|1872\n|Public\n|3,000\n|[[Lander Bearcats|Bearcats]]\n|{{college color boxes|Lander Bearcats}}\n|1990\n|-\n!{{sort|North Carolina|[[University of North Carolina at Pembroke]]}}\n|[[Pembroke, North Carolina]]\n|1887\n|Public\n|7,698\n|[[UNC Pembroke Braves|Braves]]\n|{{college color boxes|UNC Pembroke Braves}}\n|1992\n|-\n!{{sort|North Georgia|[[University of North Georgia]]}}\n|[[Dahlonega, Georgia]]\n|1873\n|Public\n|18,782\n|[[North Georgia Nighthawks|Nighthawks]]\n|{{college color boxes|North Georgia Nighthawks}}\n|2005\n|-\n!{{sort|South Carolina-Aiken|[[University of South Carolina Aiken]]}}\n|[[Aiken, South Carolina]]\n|1961\n|Public\n|3,280\n|[[USC Aiken Pacers|Pacers]]\n|{{college color boxes|USC Aiken Pacers}}\n|1990\n|-\n![[Young Harris College]]\n|[[Young Harris, Georgia]]\n|1886\n|Private ([[United Methodist Church|United Methodist]])\n|1,120\n|[[Young Harris Mountain Lions|Mountain Lions]]\n|{{college color boxes|Young Harris Mountain Lions}}\n|2012\n|}\n\n===Affiliate members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colors\n!Joined\n!Sport\n!Primary<br>Conference\n|-\n![[Albany State University]]\n|[[Albany, Georgia]]\n|1903\n|[[Public university|Public]]\n|6,371\n|[[Albany_State_Golden_Rams|Golden Rams]]\n|{{college color boxes|<br>{{color box|#0058A9}}&nbsp;{{color box|#E4A11B}}\n|2019\n|nowrap|Soccer (W)\n|[[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|SIAC]]\n|-\n![[Claflin University]]\n|[[Orangeburg, South Carolina]]\n|1869\n|[[Private university|Private]]<br>([[United Methodist Church|United Methodist]])\n|1,978\n|[[Claflin Panthers|Panthers]]\n|{{Color box|orange|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|maroon|border=darkgray}}\n|2019\n|nowrap|Baseball\n|[[Central Intercollegiate Athletic Association|CIAA]]\n|-\n![[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University, Daytona Beach|Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]]\n|[[Daytona Beach, Florida]]\n|1926\n|Private<br>([[Nonsectarian]])\n|6,794\n|[[Embry\u2013Riddle Eagles|Eagles]]\n|{{college color boxes|Embry\u2013Riddle Eagles}}\n|2017\n|nowrap|track & field outdoor (M);<br>track & field outdoor (W)\n|[[Sunshine State Conference|Sunshine State]]\n|-\n![[Florida Institute of Technology]]\n|[[Melbourne, Florida]]\n|1958\n|Private<br>(Nonsectarian)\n|8,985\n|[[Florida Tech Panthers|Panthers]]\n|{{college color boxes|Florida Tech Panthers}}\n|2014\n|track & field outdoor (M);<br>track & field outdoor (W)\n|[[Sunshine State Conference|Sunshine State]]\n|-\n![[Nova Southeastern University]]\n|[[Davie, Florida]]\n|1964\n|Private<br>(Nonsectarian)\n|33,135\n|[[Nova Southeastern Sharks|Sharks]]\n|{{college color boxes|Nova Southeastern Sharks}}\n|2012\n|track & field outdoor (M);<br>track & field outdoor (W)\n|[[Sunshine State Conference|Sunshine State]]\n|}\n\n===Former members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Nickname\n!Joined\n!Left\n!Current<br>Conference\n|-\n![[Armstrong State University]]\n|[[Savannah, Georgia]]\n|1935\n|[[Public university|Public]]\n|[[Armstrong State Pirates and Lady Pirates|Pirates]]\n|1990\n|2017\n|Merged in 2017 