{"title_page": "Chesapeake Bay Bridge", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Chesapeake Bay Bridge\u2013Tunnel}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n| image = Chesapeake Bay Bridge viewed from Sandy Point State Park.jpg\n| image_size=300px\n| caption = Both spans of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge (Gov. William Preston Lane Memorial Bridge) as seen from [[Sandy Point State Park]]\n| official_name = Gov. [[William Preston Lane Jr.]] Memorial Bridge\n| also_known_as = \"Bay Bridge\", \"Maryland Bay Bridge\",\"America's Scariest Bridge\"\n| carries = 5 lanes of {{jct|state=MD|US|50|US|301}}<br> 2 eastbound, 2 westbound, 2 reversible; either span can support 2-way traffic if the other span is completely closed)(Usually eastbound 2-way traffic is at night and westbound 2-way traffic is during the day)\n| crosses = [[Chesapeake Bay]]\n| locale = [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel]] and [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's Counties]], [[Maryland]]\n| maint = [[Maryland Transportation Authority]], [[Maryland|State of Maryland]]\n| id = AAZ050<ref name=HLR-AA>{{cite web |author = [[Maryland State Highway Administration]] |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/performTrafficStudies/dataAndStats/hwyLocationRef/2008_hlr_all/co02.pdf |format = PDF |title = Highway Location Reference: Anne Arundel County |access-date = February 24, 2010 |year = 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=HLR-QA>{{cite web |author = [[Maryland State Highway Administration]] |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/performTrafficStudies/dataAndStats/hwyLocationRef/2008_hlr_all/co17.pdf |format = PDF |title = Highway Location Reference: Queen Anne's County |access-date = February 24, 2010 |year = 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| design = [[Cantilever bridge]] (eastbound), [[Continuous truss bridge]] (westbound), and [[Suspension bridge]]s (both spans)\n| material = [[steel]], [[concrete]]\n| mainspan = {{convert|1600|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|22790|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n or {{convert|4.316|mi|km|abbr=on}} <!-- See [[Talk:Chesapeake Bay Bridge#Dimensions]] -->\n| width = {{convert|28|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} (eastbound)<br/>{{convert|38|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} (westbound)\n| clearance =\n| below = {{convert|186|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| traffic = 61,000\n| open = {{start date and age|1952|July|30|mf=yes}} (eastbound)<br />{{start date and age|1973|June|28|mf=yes}} (westbound)\n| closed =\n| toll = $4.00 (2-axle, cash/non-Md E-Z Pass)<br />\n$2.50 (2-axle, Maryland E-Z Pass)\nApplies eastbound only; no toll westbound\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|59|30|N|76|22|20|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark_scale:50000|display=title,inline}}\n|mapframe_zoom = 10\n|mapframe_caption = {{Location map|USA Maryland\n|border=infobox\n|float=center\n|label = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n|position = bottom\n|lon_dir = W\n|lat_dir = N\n|lat_deg = 38\n|lat_min = 59\n|lat_sec = 30\n|lon_deg = 76\n|lon_min = 22\n|lon_sec = 20\n|width = 250\n|caption = Location on a map of Maryland\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Chesapeake Bay Bridge''' (known locally as the \"'''Bay Bridge'''\") is a major [[twin bridges|dual-span bridge]] in the U.S. state of [[Maryland]]. Spanning the [[Chesapeake Bay]], it connects the state's rural [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]] region with the urban [[Western Shore of Maryland|Western Shore]]. The original span, opened in 1952 and with a length of {{convert|4.3|mi|km}}, was the world's longest continuous over-water steel structure. The parallel span was added in 1973. The bridge is officially named the '''Gov. William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge''' after [[William Preston Lane Jr.]] who, as the 52nd [[Governor of Maryland]], initiated its construction in the late 1940s finally after decades of political indecision and public controversy.\n\nThe bridge is part of [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland|U.S. Route 50]] (US&nbsp;50) and [[U.S. Route 301 in Maryland|US&nbsp;301]], and serves as a vital link in both routes. As part of cross-country US&nbsp;50, it connects the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]] with [[Ocean City, Maryland]], [[Rehoboth Beach, Delaware]], and other coastal tourist resort destinations. As part of US&nbsp;301, it serves as part of an alternative route for [[Interstate 95]] travelers, between northern [[Delaware]] and the [[Washington, D.C.]], area. Because of this linkage, the bridge is busy and has become known as a point of [[traffic congestion]], particularly during peak hours and summer months.\n\n==History==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:William Preston Lane on Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|William Preston Lane Jr. (1892\u20131967), 52nd Governor of Maryland for whom the bridge is named, stands on the original span shortly after construction was finished in July 1952.{{ffdc|1=William Preston Lane on Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|log=2017 November 16|date=November 2017}}]] -->\n\n===Proposals and ferries===\nStudies exploring the possibility of building a bridge across the Chesapeake Bay may have been conducted as early as the 1880s.<ref name=\"factsheet\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/Documents/baybridge.pdf |title = The William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge |access-date = October 26, 2007 |format = PDF |publisher = [[Maryland Transportation Authority]] }}</ref>\n\nThe first known proposal came about in 1907 and called for a crossing between [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] and [[Tolchester Beach, Maryland|Tolchester Beach]]; other proposals, occurring in the years 1918, 1919, 1926, and 1935, also called for a bridge in this location.<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\">{{cite web |last = Kozel |first = Scott |url = http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesa_Bay_Bridge_History.html |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge History |access-date = October 26, 2007 |work = Roads to the Future }}{{sps|certain=y|date=July 2017}}</ref> In 1927, local businesspeople were authorized to finance the construction of a Baltimore to Tolchester Beach crossing. Plans for the new bridge were made, but construction was canceled following the [[Wall Street Crash 1929|Stock Market Crash of 1929]] with the collapse of the American economy and resulting [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s.<ref name=\"factsheet\" />\n\nFerries were used as the main mode of transportation across the bay from the colonial period until the completion of the 1952 bridge. The first service ran from [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] to [[Broad Creek, Maryland|Broad Creek]] on [[Kent Island, Maryland|Kent Island]], roughly where the bridge is today.<ref name=\"MDOE-KI\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdoe.org/kentisland.html |title = Kent Island |last = Gayman |first = Jennifer |publisher = Maryland Online Encyclopedia |access-date = November 18, 2007 }}</ref> In 1919, the [[Claiborne\u2013Annapolis Ferry Company]] began running ferries between [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] and [[Claiborne, Maryland|Claiborne]], a community near [[St. Michaels, Maryland|St. Michaels]].\n\nIn July 1930, the Claiborne\u2013Annapolis Company added a new ferry route, one running from Annapolis to [[Matapeake, Maryland|Matapeake]], a significantly shorter distance. The auto and passenger ferries were taken over by the [[Maryland State Highway Administration|State Roads Commission]] in 1941 (reorganized into today's State Highway Administration of the [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] in 1973). Two years later the commission moved the western terminus of the old [[Annapolis\u2013Matapeake ferry]] to Sandy Point (later adjacent to [[Sandy Point State Park]]), shortening the cross-bay trip.\n\n===Construction of 1952 span===\nA 1938 proposal by the [[Maryland General Assembly]] was the first to call for a bridge at the Sandy Point\u2013Kent Island location.<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\" /> Although the legislation authorizing the new bridge passed, the involvement of the United States in World War II delayed the bridge's construction. In 1947, with the war over, the Assembly, under the leadership of Maryland Governor [[William Preston Lane Jr.]], (1892\u20131967), passed legislation directing the old State Roads Commission to begin construction.<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> Ground was broken in January 1949, and after a {{frac|3|1|2}}-year construction project, the bridge opened to traffic on July 30, 1952, as both the longest continuous over-water steel structure, and the third longest bridge in the world.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-engineering feats\">{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bay Bridge: Engineering Feats |publisher = baybridge.com |access-date = February 5, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080701104825/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid= |archive-date = July 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Before the opening, a parade of vehicles made the first official crossing, led by then current Governor [[Theodore McKeldin|Theodore Roosevelt McKeldin]], (1900\u20131974), and other state officials in a distinctive white Cadillac convertible flying huge American and Maryland flags.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-history\">{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bay Bridge: History |publisher = baybridge.com |access-date = February 5, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080701104741/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid= |archive-date = July 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> On November 9, 1967, the bridge was dedicated to Governor Lane, who had died earlier that year, and officially renamed the \"William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge\".\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Line for Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Lines before Second Bay Bridge was built]] -->\n\n===1973 expansion===\nIn 1967, due to increasing traffic volumes, the Maryland General Assembly authorized three possible new crossings, all suggested during the [[1964 Chesapeake Bay crossing study]].<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\" /> These included one further north near [[Baltimore]], one in [[southern Maryland]], and an additional span to be added to the existing bridge from Kent Island to Sandy Point; ultimately, the third option was chosen. Construction of the new parallel span began in 1969 to the north of the original bridge, and it was completed on June 28, 1973.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-history\" />\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge sign placement.jpg|thumb|right|sign replacement]] -->\n\n===Notable incidents===\n[[File:Looking up Chesapeake Bay Bridge during Isabel, Sept 18, 2003.jpg|thumb|right|The Bay Bridge during 2003's [[Hurricane Isabel]].]]\n[[File:Police block traffic to Chesapeake Bay Bridge during Isabel, Sept 18 2003.jpg|thumb|right|Police block traffic leading up to the Bay Bridge during [[Hurricane Isabel]] due to high winds.]]\nBecause of its height, the narrowness of the spans (there are no hard shoulders), the low guardrails, and the frequency of high winds, it is known as one of the scariest bridges in the world,<ref>{{cite web |title = World's Scariest Bridges |url = http://www.travelandleisure.com/articles/worlds-scariest-bridges/9 |publisher = Travel and Leisure |date = October 2010 |access-date = September 2, 2013 }}</ref> especially in higher tractor-trailer trucks.<ref>{{cite news |title = Don't look down! The Maryland bridge so terrifying locals pay $25 to be driven across in their own car |url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2331679/Chesapeake-Bay-bridge-The-Maryland-bridge-terrifying-locals-pay-25-company-shuttle-car.html |newspaper = [[Daily Mail]] |date = 27 May 2013 |access-date = September 2, 2013 }}</ref> Several incidents have caused significant closures and [[traffic congestion]] on either side approaching the bridge.\n\nThe bridge has been closed four times due to extreme weather. The first time was September 18, 2003, during [[Hurricane Isabel]] and its high winds.<ref>{{cite news |title = Hurricane Isabel photo log |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/forcesofnature/isabel_photolog.html |work = Indepth:Forces of Nature |publisher = [[CBC News]] |date = September 18, 2003 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = US: Millions still without power a week after Hurricane Isabel |url = http://www.wsws.org/articles/2003/sep2003/isab-s25.shtml |last = Martin |first = Patrick |publisher = [[World Socialist Website]] |date = September 25, 2003 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref> On August 27, 2011, the bridge was closed to all traffic due to the impact of [[Hurricane Irene]]. Then-Governor [[Martin O'Malley]] ordered the bridge closed when sustained winds exceeded {{convert|55|mph|km/h}}. On October 29, 2012, the bridge was closed due to the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]].<ref>{{cite web |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge Now Closed |url = http://www.wboc.com/story/19944902/chesapeake-bay-bridge-now-clo |publisher = WBOC TV |access-date = October 29, 2012 }}</ref> On March 6, 2013, during the [[March 2013 nor'easter]], high winds again caused the bridge to be closed.<ref>{{cite web |title = High winds force closure of Chesapeake Bay Bridge |url = http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20130306/NEWS/130306014/High-winds-force-closure-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge |publisher = Delaware Online |date = March 6, 2013 |access-date = March 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2008, a tractor trailer involved in a head-on collision near the west end fell from the bridge; the driver died in the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081100422.html?nav=hcmodule |title = Traffic Continues to Stall on Bay Bridge |last1 = St. George |first1 = Donna |last2 = Birnbaum |first2 = Michael |newspaper = The Washington Post |date = August 11, 2008 |access-date = August 11, 2008 |postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> The incident has highlighted concern that the bridge may not be structurally safe, but the [[Maryland Transportation Authority]] (MDTA) has discounted any structural or engineering problems with it.<ref name=\"structsafe-wjz\">{{cite news |url = http://wjz.com/local/bay.bridge.crash.2.792465.html |title = Eastbound Right Lane Reopens On Bay Bridge |last = May |first = Adam |date = August 11, 2008 |work = WJZ |access-date = August 12, 2008 }}</ref><!-- most of the content of the WJZ cite is derived from the AP cite without mentioning this fact --> Inspections of the wall in the weeks following the accident revealed that there was deterioration in the form of corrosion of the steel reinforcements inside barriers; this prompted immediate repairs to the wall.<ref>{{cite news |first = Alex |last = Dominguez |title = Bay Bridge walls had corrosion, tests show |url = http://fredericksburg.com//News/FLS/2008/082008/08272008/405943 |newspaper = The Free Lance-Star |date = August 27, 2008 |access-date = August 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508063111/http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2008/082008/08272008/405943 |archivedate = May 8, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Specifications and operations==\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge from Sandy Point State Park.jpg|thumb|Chesapeake Bay Bridge from Sandy Point State Park]]\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge MD1.jpg|thumb|right|View of both spans from the [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]] side, in which the original 1952 span appears in front of the newer 1973 span.]]\nWith shore-to-shore lengths of {{convert|4.33|and|4.35|mi|km}},<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> the two spans of the bridge form the longest fixed water crossing in Maryland and ranked 102nd among the world's [[List of bridges by length|longest over-water structures]]. The bridge's western terminus is in [[Sandy Point State Park]], located northeast of [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] in [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel County]], and its eastern terminus is in [[Stevensville, Maryland|Stevensville]] on [[Kent Island, Maryland|Kent Island]] in [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]].[[File:20030519BayBridge.jpg|thumb|left|A May 2003 sunset behind the Bay Bridge]]\n\n===Structural details===\nWith the exception of the number of lanes on each (two on the original span and three on the newer span) and differences owing to the design standards for the periods in which they were built, the spans are structurally similar. Both were designed by [[J. E. Greiner Company]],<ref>{{Cite book |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/maintainRoadsBridges/bridges/oppe/bridgebook/bridge_book.asp |last1 = Legler |first1 = Dixie |last2 = Highsmith |first2 = Carol |year = 2002 |title = Historic Bridges of Maryland |pages = 46 |location = Crownsville, Md. |publisher = Maryland Historic Trust |isbn = 1-878399-80-2 |postscript   =|url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090510070141/http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/maintainRoadsBridges/bridges/oppe/bridgebook/bridge_book.asp |archivedate = 2009-05-10 |df = }}</ref> which later became a part of [[AECOM]] through the company's acquisition of [[URS Corporation]]. Each span features:\n*Two main spans over the bay's two shipping channels:\n**A {{convert|3200|ft|m|0|adj=on}} [[Suspension bridge|suspension]] span over the western channel with a maximum clearance of {{convert|186|ft|m|1}}\u2014high enough to accommodate ocean-going vessels and [[tall ship]]s\n**A through-truss [[Cantilever bridge|cantilever]] span over the eastern channel with a maximum clearance of {{convert|58|ft|m}}\n*Deck truss and steel girder spans flanking the main spans\n*Concrete beam spans on the portions closest to the shores\n*A curve near the western terminus, which is required so that the main spans cross the bay's shipping channels at 90 degrees per [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] requirements<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge: Fun Facts [Family Fun] |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = October 9, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928035027/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid= |archive-date = September 28, 2007 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Traffic control===\n[[File:Chesapeake bay bridge sunset.jpg|200px|thumb|left|The westbound span at sunset. The leftmost lane is closed to westbound traffic.]]\nTraffic patterns on the bridge's five lanes can be adjusted via its [[reversible lane|lane control]] system, which consists of overhead lane control signals on both spans and approaches. Typically, the two lanes on the south-most span are configured for vehicles traveling east on eastbound US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301, while the three lanes on the north-most span are configured for vehicles traveling west on westbound US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301; the spans are therefore referred to as the \"eastbound span\" and \"westbound span\", respectively. However, this pattern is adjusted during incidents or peak travel times: for instance, on the outset of weekends when there is a high volume of beach-bound traffic, one lane on the westbound span is configured for eastbound traffic.\n\nIn 2006, pink markers were placed along the eastbound span to mark out the suggested following distance, similar to systems used in [[Minnesota]] and [[Pennsylvania]]. The markers are a part of the MDTA's \"Pace Your Space\" campaign to prevent [[car accident|vehicle collisions]] and [[traffic congestion]] due to [[tailgating]] on the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridgeproject.com/safetytips.html |title = SAFETY TIPS for traveling the Bay Bridge |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227222434/http://www.baybridgeproject.com/safetytips.html |archivedate = December 27, 2007 |df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.stateline.org/live/details/story?contentId=125133 |title = State DOTs hope drivers see dots |last = Gramlich |first = John |publisher = Stateline.Org |date = July 7, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, changes were made to increase safety on the westbound span during two-way operations: signs, pavement markings, and rumble strips were modified, and a buffer zone between the left and center lanes was created. As a result, motorists can no longer switch between the left and center lanes, whether or not two-way operations are in effect.<ref>{{cite web |title = Plans made to enhance two-way traffic operations on Chesapeake Bay Bridge |url = http://www.wbaltv.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel-county/Plans-made-to-enhance-two-way-traffic-operations-on-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge/-/10137088/19805934/-/stpg8kz/-/index.html |publisher = WBAL TV |access-date = June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130620022345/http://www.wbaltv.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel-county/Plans-made-to-enhance-two-way-traffic-operations-on-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge/-/10137088/19805934/-/stpg8kz/-/index.html |archivedate = June 20, 2013 |df   =}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last = Thomson |first = Candy |title = Bay Bridge getting rumble strips, safety buffer zone |url = http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/breaking/bs-md-bay-bridge-safety-20130418,0,7871261.story |newspaper = Baltimore Sun |access-date = June 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Tolls and fees===\n\nOperated by the MDTA, the bridge has a one-way toll (eastbound) of $4.00 for two-axle vehicles; vehicles with a Maryland [[E-ZPass]] pay $2.50.<ref>{{cite web |title = Toll Rates |url = http://www.baybridge.maryland.gov/toll-rates |website = baybridge.maryland.gov |access-date = June 11, 2017 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref> Previously the bridge had a one-way (eastbound) toll of $6.00 for two-axle vehicles (raised from $4 on July 1, 2013); vehicles with E-ZPass that were enrolled in the Bay Bridge Commuter Plan paid $2.10 (raised from $1 on July 1, 2013).<ref>{{cite web |title = Toll Rates for the William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial (Bay) Bridge (US 50/301) |url = http://www.mdta.maryland.gov/TollRates/baybridge_rates.html |access-date = July 10, 2014 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref>\n\nTolls were collected in both directions until April 1989, when tolls were doubled and only collected in the Eastbound direction.<ref>{{cite news |title=WESTBOUND BAY BRIDGE TOLL ENDING |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1989/02/01/westbound-bay-bridge-toll-ending/82181e67-d90e-48f0-b3d3-f9e111731782 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=Feb 1, 1989}}</ref>\n\nThe MDTA contracts with private companies to provide transportation across the bridge for nervous drivers ([[gephyrophobia]]cs) and cyclists; fees are $25 and $30 for drivers and cyclists, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24&Itemid= |title = Safe Travel Tips |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = November 30, 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091006060747/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24&Itemid= |archive-date = October 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Bay Bridge Walk and Run==\nWhile there are no pedestrian facilities on the bridge, the Bay Bridge Walk and Governor's Bay Bridge Run used to afford an opportunity to cross the bridge on foot, usually on the first Sunday in May.<ref name=release>{{cite press release |title = Governor O'Malley Announces Plans to Host 2007 Bay Bridge Walk |publisher = Maryland Department of Transportation |date = February 23, 2007 |url = http://www.e-mdot.com/News/2007/February%202007/Bay%20Bridge%20walk.htm |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121154709/http://www.e-mdot.com/News/2007/February%202007/Bay%20Bridge%20walk.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date = November 21, 2008 |access-date = September 1, 2008 |quote = The first Sunday in May means Bay Bridge Walk }}</ref> The events took place on the eastbound span, which was closed to vehicles while two-way traffic shared the westbound span. Participants started on the east end of the bridge (on Kent Island) and proceeded west to the finish near the toll plaza. [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority|WMATA]] and [[Maryland Transit Administration|MTA]] transit buses transported participants between outlying parking areas and the start and finish points.\n\nThe run, a [[10,000 metres|10K]] race across the bridge, is held early in the morning before the walk. It is conducted by the Annapolis Striders, a local running organization, and controlled by the MDTA and [[Maryland Department of Natural Resources]]. Proceeds went to the Chesapeake Bay Trust in support of the bay.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://annapolisstriders.org/gbbrInfo2007.htm |title = The 22nd Governor\u2019s Bay Bridge Run |access-date = November 16, 2007 |publisher = Annapolis Striders |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055606/http://annapolisstriders.org/gbbrInfo2007.htm |archivedate = October 27, 2007 |df = }}</ref>\n\nThe walk was first held in 1975,<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-walk\">{{cite web |url = http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesa_Bay_Bridge_Walk.html |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge Walk |last = Kozel |first = Scott |access-date = November 16, 2007 |work = Roads to the Future }}</ref> after a [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scout]] leader in [[Towson, Maryland|Towson]] asked then-Governor [[Marvin Mandel]] if his troop could walk across the bridge while it was closed for maintenance.<ref name=release /> The annual walk was canceled for the first time in 1980 due to poor weather conditions, and later saw frequent cancellations throughout the 2000s. During this period the walk was canceled in:\n*2002 and 2007 due to poor weather conditions.<ref name=\"WJZ-2007 walk cancelled\">{{cite news |title = High Winds Cancel Bay Bridge Walk |last = Schuyler |first = Jim |url = http://wjz.com/topstories/local_story_126105130.html |publisher = [[WJZ-TV]] |date = May 6, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227223020/http://wjz.com/topstories/local_story_126105130.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archive-date = December 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post: race canceled\">{{cite news |title = Race Canceled for 4th Time in Six Years |last = Yanovits |first = Dave |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/06/AR2007050601014.html |newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] |date = May 7, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n*2003 and 2005 due to security concerns.<ref name=\"Washington Post: race canceled\" />\n*2008, 2009, and 2010 due to construction activity in the area on the west side of the bridge where participants would otherwise be staged.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.wtop.com/?nid=715&sid=1305650 |title = Bay Bridge Walk Canceled for 2008, 2009 |date = December 6, 2007 |publisher = WTOP News |access-date = February 6, 2008 }}</ref> Fiscal concerns were also cited as a contributing factor to the 2010 cancellation.<ref>{{Cite journal |url = http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=598&sid=1903428 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130105104839/http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=598&sid=1903428 |url-status=dead |archive-date = January 5, 2013 |publisher = WTOP |last = Basch |first = Michelle |title = Bay Bridge Walk cancelled for 4th year in a row |accessdate = March 14, 2010 |postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref>\n*2011 due to fiscal concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid= |title = Bay Bridge |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |author = Eric Willison |date = April 14, 2015 |work = baybridge.com |access-date = March 31, 2011 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110303041037/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid= |archive-date = March 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n*2012 for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |title = No Bridge Walk Scheduled in 2012 |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20120904071539/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17 |url-status=dead |archive-date = 2012-09-04 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref>\n\nFollowing its cancellation in 2005, the MDTA considered decreasing the annual frequency of the event, citing traffic, fiscal, manpower, and security concerns. The most recent event (held in 2006) cost over $350,000, and the cost estimate for 2012 was almost $400,000. In late 2011, a non-profit group, the [[Greater Washington Sports Alliance]] (GWSA), approached the MDTA Capital Committee to propose sponsoring the event, along with a concert at Sandy Point State Park, at no cost to the MDTA. While the Capital Committee unanimously recommended that the MDTA Board approve the proposal contingent upon an agreement between the GWSA and the MDTA, the 2012 event was ultimately cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title = Monthly Capital Meeting Minutes for October 13, 2011 |url = http://www.mdta.maryland.gov/MeetingSchedules/Meeting_Minutes/CapComm_Minutes_10-13-2011.pdf |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAfter increasingly consistent cancellations of the walking event, the MDTA, along with [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]], contracted with an outside company to have a professional 10K race across the bridge, which has been labeled the \"Across the Bay 10K\". The inaugural event occurred November 9, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://delmarvatowncrier.com/archives/just-announced-10k-race-across-the-chesapeake-bay-bridge/ |title = Just Announced: 10K Race Across the Chesapeake Bay Bridge |date = March 27, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |newspaper = Delmarva Town Crier }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.myeasternshoremd.com/news/queen_annes_county/article_5336e54c-9bba-11e2-a5f5-0019bb2963f4.html |title = Officials say OK to bridge 10K |date = April 2, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |first = Jordan |last = Shatz }}</ref> The Race Director is [[Dave McGillivray]],<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.runningusa.org/10K-across-the-bay-dmse-mcgillivray?returnTo=2013 |title = McGillivray to Direct 10K Across the Bay |newspaper = Running USA |date = July 17, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140727220639/http://www.runningusa.org/10K-across-the-bay-dmse-mcgillivray?returnTo=2013 |archivedate = July 27, 2014 |df   =}}</ref> who has served in that capacity for the BAA Boston Marathon since 1988. The Across the Bay 10K will have several charity beneficiaries, including bay research and restoration as well as breast cancer research and several others.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwfitness/article/Registration-Opens-for-Across-the-Bay-10K-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge-Run-Today-20131108 |title = Registration Opens for 'Across the Bay 10K' Chesapeake Bay Bridge Run Today |date = November 9, 2013 |access-date = December 5, 2013 |publisher = Wisdom Digital Media |quote = Runners are encouraged to fundraise for charity and last week two charities were selected to benefit from the race |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140729171707/http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwfitness/article/Registration-Opens-for-Across-the-Bay-10K-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge-Run-Today-20131108 |archive-date = 2014-07-29 |url-status=dead |df   =}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Race Charity Partners |url = http://bridgerace.com/official-partners.php |access-date = December 5, 2013 |publisher = CBBR |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131115064907/http://www.bridgerace.com/official-partners.php |archivedate = November 15, 2013 |df = }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Ocean City MD beach looking north from pier.jpeg|thumb|left|In the years since the bridge's completion, Ocean City (pictured) has experienced significant growth.]]\nSince its construction, the bridge has made significant impacts on both sides of the bay; among them has been the growth of [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]] communities. When the bridge opened in 1952, and again when the second span was added in 1973, the Eastern Shore was given easier access to [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], causing areas in southern [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]] to develop as [[commuter town|bedroom communities]]. This extension of the Baltimore\u2013Washington suburbs has led Queen Anne's County to be listed as part of the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Metropolitan Area]]. The bridge has also given easier access to [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]] from the [[Western Shore]], which has caused Ocean City to grow from a small town to one that is said to become the second largest city in Maryland during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?pagename=article&node=&contentId=A18858-2002Jul29&notFound=true |title = Spanning Half a Century |last = Johnson |first = Darragh |author2 = Hernandez, Nelson |newspaper = The Washington Post |date = July 30, 2002 |access-date = October 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, the impending completion of the bridge gave rise to an extension of [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland|US&nbsp;50]] to Ocean City.<ref>{{cite web |title = End of U.S. highway 50 |url = http://www.geocities.com/usend5059/End050/end050.htm |date = August 10, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090729182235/http://geocities.com/usend5059/End050/end050.htm |archive-date = July 29, 2009 }}</ref> The route was extended along the corridor of [[Maryland Route 404]] (MD&nbsp;404) and a large portion of [[U.S. Route 213|US&nbsp;213]], cutting both of those routes back. During the 1950s, US&nbsp;50 on the Western Shore was rerouted onto the long-proposed [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland#John Hanson Highway|Annapolis\u2013Washington Expressway]] (now known as the John Hanson Highway), which was built at the time in order to provide better access to the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.dcroads.net/roads/I-595_MD/ |title = John Hanson Highway |last = Anderson |first = Steve |publisher = dcroads.net |access-date = February 6, 2008 }}</ref> As the Eastern Shore, particularly Ocean City, grew, further upgrades and realignments of US&nbsp;50 took place. This work included the aforementioned 1973 completion of the second Bay Bridge span, the extension of the US&nbsp;50 freeway eastward to the US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301 split in [[Queenstown, Maryland|Queenstown]], and the construction of a freeway bypass around the north side of Salisbury in 2002. Additionally, the road has been upgraded and realigned over the years from its original two-lane configuration to a four-lane [[divided highway]], with the last such section being in [[Vienna, Maryland|Vienna]], bypassed in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.delmarvahighways.com/old50-vienna.htm |title = Abandoned US 50 / US 213, Vienna, MD |last = Dukes |first = Corey |publisher = Delmarva Highways |date = August 1, 2007 |accessdate = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071020050833/http://www.delmarvahighways.com/old50-vienna.htm |archivedate = October 20, 2007 |df   =}}</ref> As of 2008, there are plans for further upgrades to US&nbsp;50, including extending its freeway portion in Queen Anne's County to MD&nbsp;404 outside of [[Wye Mills, Maryland|Wye Mills]] and replacing the aging [[Harry W. Kelly Memorial Bridge]] into Ocean City.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.delmarvahighways.com/us50.htm |title = Ocean Gateway \u2013 Ocean City, MD to MD 90 Interchange |last = Dukes |first = Corey |publisher = Delmarva Highways |date = January 19, 2004 |access-date = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927045828/http://www.delmarvahighways.com/us50.htm |archive-date = September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is often the site of [[Suicide bridge|suicides]] by jumpers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecildaily.com/local_news/police-confirm-the-identity-of-bridge-jumper/article_7e334ff8-f529-11e0-bafd-001cc4c03286.html|title=Police confirm the identity of bridge jumper|first=Carl Hamilton|last=cahamilton@ceciwhig.com|website=Cecil Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecildaily.com/news/state_news/one-man-dies-another-injured-in-jumps-from-bay-bridge/article_bdaac432-0fbd-11e1-8f66-001cc4c03286.html|title=One man dies, another injured in jumps from Bay Bridge|website=Cecil Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbc26.com/news/national/maryland-first-responder-saves-man-from-suicide-on-chesapeake-bay-bridge|title=First responder saves man from suicide on bridge|date=12 April 2018|website=WGBA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/nov/30/man-jumps-chesapeake-bay-bridge/|title=Man jumps off Chesapeake Bay Bridge in Maryland|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|website=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/3-plunge-from-bay-bridge-2-killed|title=3 plunge from Bay Bridge; 2 killed|date=18 April 2011|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n==Future expansion==\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge Aerial.jpg|thumb|Chesapeake Bay Bridge]]\n\n{{main|2005 Chesapeake Bay crossing study}}\nIn December 2004, a study concluded that traffic across the bridge was expected to increase by 40% by 2025. The following year, a task force formed by Governor [[Robert Ehrlich|Bob Ehrlich]] met to again explore the possibility of establishing a new Chesapeake Bay crossing.<ref name=\"second bridge\">{{cite news |last = Berman |first = Dori |url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4183/is_20050627/ai_n14693744 |title = Task force says second Chesapeake Bay bridge is best option |publisher = The Baltimore Daily Record |date = June 27, 2005 |access-date = February 5, 2008 }}</ref> The task force concluded that a bridge would be the best option for an additional crossing, and four geographic locations for such a bridge were explored: Baltimore County to Kent County, Anne Arundel County to Queen Anne's County (the existing location), Anne Arundel or Calvert County to Talbot County, and Calvert County to Dorchester County.<ref name=\"task force pdf\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/BayCrossing/BriefingBook/Taskforce_Briefing_Book_2-001.pdf |title = Meeting #2: Bridge, Traffic, and Highway Issues |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = February 5, 2008 |format = pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070124043621/http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/BayCrossing/BriefingBook/Taskforce_Briefing_Book_2-001.pdf |archive-date = January 24, 2007 }}</ref> In late 2006, the task force released a report on the study but did not make a final recommendation; members of the task force requested additional time to continue the study.<ref name=\"WTOP-report released\">{{cite news |last = Wyatt |first = Kristen |url = http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=25&sid=896776 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130105084049/http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=25&sid=896776 |url-status=dead |archive-date = January 5, 2013 |title = Bay Bridge Report Released without Recommendation |publisher = WTOP news |date = August 29, 2006 |access-date = February 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|Chesaspeake Bay Bridge Panorama 60465636.jpg|900px|Panoramic view of the bridge, looking south, in which the two main spans (suspension at center and through truss at left) are visible. The towers with the \"X\"-shaped latticework are on the eastbound (1952) suspension span, while those with the horizontal crossmembers are on the westbound (1973) suspension span. Notice the difference in the locations of the anchoring points of the main cables: at water level for the eastbound span and at deck level atop large concrete piers for the westbound span.}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Maryland}}\n*[[Kent Narrows Bridge]]\n*[[List of bridges by length]]\n*[[Severn River Bridge]]\n*[[St. Margaret's, Maryland]]\n*[[Cape St. Claire, Maryland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chesapeake Bay Bridge}}\n*{{osmrelation|1736026}}\n*[http://www.baybridge.com Chesapeake Bay Bridge official website]\n*[http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/servlet/dispatchServlet?url=/TollFacilities/BayBridge.jsp Bay Bridge Page at MdTA website]\n*[http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesapeake_Bay_Bridge.html Roads to the Future website]\n*[http://www.dcroads.net/crossings/bay-bridge/ Page at dcroads.net]\n*{{Structurae|id=20000561|title=Chesapeake Bay Bridge}}\n*[http://www.chart.state.md.us/video/videolow.asp?feed=24 Live Video Rt 50 Kent Island]\n*[http://www.chart.state.md.us/video/videolow.asp?feed=2 Live Video Rt 50 Sandy Point]\n*[https://archive.org/details/probableeconomic62mary A 1950 comprehensive study of the economic effects of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge (pdf)]\n\n{{MdTA facilities}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure = Bridges\n|place = [[Chesapeake Bay]]\n|bridge = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n|bridge signs = [[File:US 50.svg|20px]] [[File:US 301.svg|25px]]\n|upstream = [[P.W. & B. Railroad Bridge]] (ruins) <br /> ([[Susquehanna River]]) <br />\n[[Francis Scott Key Bridge (Baltimore)|Francis Scott Key Bridge]] <br /> ([[Patapsco River]]) <br>\n[[File:I-695.svg|25px]] <br>\n[[Chesapeake City Bridge]] <br> ([[Chesapeake and Delaware Canal]]) <br /> [[File:MD Route 213.svg|25px]]\n|downstream = [[Chesapeake Bay Bridge\u2013Tunnel]]\n|downstream signs = [[File:US 13.svg|20px]]\n}}\n\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1952]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1973]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Queen Anne's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the United States Numbered Highways]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chesapeake Bay]]\n[[Category:Concrete bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Girder bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Intracoastal Waterway]]\n[[Category:Towers in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suspension bridges in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Through arch bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Maryland]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 50]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 301]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Chesapeake Bay Bridge\u2013Tunnel}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n| image = Chesapeake Bay Bridge viewed from Sandy Point State Park.jpg\n| image_size=300px\n| caption = Both spans of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge (Gov. William Preston Lane Memorial Bridge) as seen from [[Sandy Point State Park]]\n| official_name = Gov. [[William Preston Lane Jr.]] Memorial Bridge\n| also_known_as = \"Bay Bridge\", \"Maryland Bay Bridge\",\"America's Scariest Bridge\"\n| carries = 5 lanes of {{jct|state=MD|US|50|US|301}}<br> 2 eastbound, 2 westbound, 2 reversible; either span can support 2-way traffic if the other span is completely closed)(Usually eastbound 2-way traffic is at night and westbound 2-way traffic is during the day)\n| crosses = [[Chesapeake Bay]]\n| locale = [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel]] and [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's Counties]], [[Maryland]]\n| maint = [[Maryland Transportation Authority]], [[Maryland|State of Maryland]]\n| id = AAZ050<ref name=HLR-AA>{{cite web |author = [[Maryland State Highway Administration]] |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/performTrafficStudies/dataAndStats/hwyLocationRef/2008_hlr_all/co02.pdf |format = PDF |title = Highway Location Reference: Anne Arundel County |access-date = February 24, 2010 |year = 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=HLR-QA>{{cite web |author = [[Maryland State Highway Administration]] |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/performTrafficStudies/dataAndStats/hwyLocationRef/2008_hlr_all/co17.pdf |format = PDF |title = Highway Location Reference: Queen Anne's County |access-date = February 24, 2010 |year = 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| design = [[Cantilever bridge]] (eastbound), [[Continuous truss bridge]] (westbound), and [[Suspension bridge]]s (both spans)\n| material = [[steel]], [[concrete]]\n| mainspan = {{convert|1600|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|22790|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n or {{convert|4.316|mi|km|abbr=on}} <!-- See [[Talk:Chesapeake Bay Bridge#Dimensions]] -->\n| width = {{convert|28|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} (eastbound)<br/>{{convert|38|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} (westbound)\n| clearance =\n| below = {{convert|186|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| traffic = 61,000\n| open = {{start date and age|1952|July|30|mf=yes}} (eastbound)<br />{{start date and age|1973|June|28|mf=yes}} (westbound)\n| closed =\n| toll = $4.00 (2-axle, cash/non-Md E-Z Pass)<br />\n$2.50 (2-axle, Maryland E-Z Pass)\nApplies eastbound only; no toll westbound\n| coordinates = {{coord|38|59|30|N|76|22|20|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark_scale:50000|display=title,inline}}\n|mapframe_zoom = 10\n|mapframe_caption = {{Location map|USA Maryland\n|border=infobox\n|float=center\n|label = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n|position = bottom\n|lon_dir = W\n|lat_dir = N\n|lat_deg = 38\n|lat_min = 59\n|lat_sec = 30\n|lon_deg = 76\n|lon_min = 22\n|lon_sec = 20\n|width = 250\n|caption = Location on a map of Maryland\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Chesapeake Bay Bridge''' (known locally as the \"'''Bay Bridge'''\") is a major [[twin bridges|dual-span bridge]] in the U.S. state of [[Maryland]]. Spanning the [[Chesapeake Bay]], it connects the state's rural [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]] region with the urban [[Western Shore of Maryland|Western Shore]]. The original span, opened in 1952 and with a length of {{convert|4.3|mi|km}}, was the world's longest continuous over-water steel structure. The parallel span was added in 1973. The bridge is officially named the '''Gov. William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge''' after [[William Preston Lane Jr.]] who, as the 52nd [[Governor of Maryland]], initiated its construction in the late 1940s finally after decades of political indecision and public controversy.\n\nThe bridge is part of [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland|U.S. Route 50]] (US&nbsp;50) and [[U.S. Route 301 in Maryland|US&nbsp;301]], and serves as a vital link in both routes. As part of cross-country US&nbsp;50, it connects the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]] with [[Ocean City, Maryland]], [[Rehoboth Beach, Delaware]], and other coastal tourist resort destinations. As part of US&nbsp;301, it serves as part of an alternative route for [[Interstate 95]] travelers, between northern [[Delaware]] and the [[Washington, D.C.]], area. Because of this linkage, the bridge is busy and has become known as a point of [[traffic congestion]], particularly during peak hours and summer months.\n\n==History==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:William Preston Lane on Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|William Preston Lane Jr. (1892\u20131967), 52nd Governor of Maryland for whom the bridge is named, stands on the original span shortly after construction was finished in July 1952.{{ffdc|1=William Preston Lane on Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|log=2017 November 16|date=November 2017}}]] -->\n\n===Proposals and ferries===\nStudies exploring the possibility of building a bridge across the Chesapeake Bay may have been conducted as early as the 1880s.<ref name=\"factsheet\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/Documents/baybridge.pdf |title = The William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge |access-date = October 26, 2007 |format = PDF |publisher = [[Maryland Transportation Authority]] }}</ref>\n\nThe first known proposal came about in 1907 and called for a crossing between [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] and [[Tolchester Beach, Maryland|Tolchester Beach]]; other proposals, occurring in the years 1918, 1919, 1926, and 1935, also called for a bridge in this location.<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\">{{cite web |last = Kozel |first = Scott |url = http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesa_Bay_Bridge_History.html |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge History |access-date = October 26, 2007 |work = Roads to the Future }}{{sps|certain=y|date=July 2017}}</ref> In 1927, local businesspeople were authorized to finance the construction of a Baltimore to Tolchester Beach crossing. Plans for the new bridge were made, but construction was canceled following the [[Wall Street Crash 1929|Stock Market Crash of 1929]] with the collapse of the American economy and resulting [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s.<ref name=\"factsheet\" />\n\nFerries were used as the main mode of transportation across the bay from the colonial period until the completion of the 1952 bridge. The first service ran from [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] to [[Broad Creek, Maryland|Broad Creek]] on [[Kent Island, Maryland|Kent Island]], roughly where the bridge is today.<ref name=\"MDOE-KI\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdoe.org/kentisland.html |title = Kent Island |last = Gayman |first = Jennifer |publisher = Maryland Online Encyclopedia |access-date = November 18, 2007 }}</ref> In 1919, the [[Claiborne\u2013Annapolis Ferry Company]] began running ferries between [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] and [[Claiborne, Maryland|Claiborne]], a community near [[St. Michaels, Maryland|St. Michaels]].\n\nIn July 1930, the Claiborne\u2013Annapolis Company added a new ferry route, one running from Annapolis to [[Matapeake, Maryland|Matapeake]], a significantly shorter distance. The auto and passenger ferries were taken over by the [[Maryland State Highway Administration|State Roads Commission]] in 1941 (reorganized into today's State Highway Administration of the [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] in 1973). Two years later the commission moved the western terminus of the old [[Annapolis\u2013Matapeake ferry]] to Sandy Point (later adjacent to [[Sandy Point State Park]]), shortening the cross-bay trip.\n\n===Construction of 1952 span===\nA 1938 proposal by the [[Maryland General Assembly]] was the first to call for a bridge at the Sandy Point\u2013Kent Island location.<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\" /> Although the legislation authorizing the new bridge passed, the involvement of the United States in World War II delayed the bridge's construction. In 1947, with the war over, the Assembly, under the leadership of Maryland Governor [[William Preston Lane Jr.]], (1892\u20131967), passed legislation directing the old State Roads Commission to begin construction.<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> Ground was broken in January 1949, and after a {{frac|3|1|2}}-year construction project, the bridge opened to traffic on July 30, 1952, as both the longest continuous over-water steel structure, and the third longest bridge in the world.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-engineering feats\">{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bay Bridge: Engineering Feats |publisher = baybridge.com |access-date = February 5, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080701104825/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28&Itemid= |archive-date = July 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Before the opening, a parade of vehicles made the first official crossing, led by then current Governor [[Theodore McKeldin|Theodore Roosevelt McKeldin]], (1900\u20131974), and other state officials in a distinctive white Cadillac convertible flying huge American and Maryland flags.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-history\">{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bay Bridge: History |publisher = baybridge.com |access-date = February 5, 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080701104741/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid= |archive-date = July 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> On November 9, 1967, the bridge was dedicated to Governor Lane, who had died earlier that year, and officially renamed the \"William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge\".\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Line for Chesapeake Bay Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|Lines before Second Bay Bridge was built]] -->\n\n===1973 expansion===\nIn 1967, due to increasing traffic volumes, the Maryland General Assembly authorized three possible new crossings, all suggested during the [[1964 Chesapeake Bay crossing study]].<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-history\" /> These included one further north near [[Baltimore]], one in [[southern Maryland]], and an additional span to be added to the existing bridge from Kent Island to Sandy Point; ultimately, the third option was chosen. Construction of the new parallel span began in 1969 to the north of the original bridge, and it was completed on June 28, 1973.<ref name=\"baybridge.com-history\" />\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge sign placement.jpg|thumb|right|sign replacement]] -->\n\n===Notable incidents===\n[[File:Looking up Chesapeake Bay Bridge during Isabel, Sept 18, 2003.jpg|thumb|right|The Bay Bridge during 2003's [[Hurricane Isabel]].]]\n[[File:Police block traffic to Chesapeake Bay Bridge during Isabel, Sept 18 2003.jpg|thumb|right|Police block traffic leading up to the Bay Bridge during [[Hurricane Isabel]] due to high winds.]]\nBecause of its height, the narrowness of the spans (there are no hard shoulders), the low guardrails, and the frequency of high winds, it is known as one of the scariest bridges in the world,<ref>{{cite web |title = World's Scariest Bridges |url = http://www.travelandleisure.com/articles/worlds-scariest-bridges/9 |publisher = Travel and Leisure |date = October 2010 |access-date = September 2, 2013 }}</ref> especially in higher tractor-trailer trucks.<ref>{{cite news |title = Don't look down! The Maryland bridge so terrifying locals pay $25 to be driven across in their own car |url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2331679/Chesapeake-Bay-bridge-The-Maryland-bridge-terrifying-locals-pay-25-company-shuttle-car.html |newspaper = [[Daily Mail]] |date = 27 May 2013 |access-date = September 2, 2013 }}</ref> Several incidents have caused significant closures and [[traffic congestion]] on either side approaching the bridge.\n\nThe bridge has been closed four times due to extreme weather. The first time was September 18, 2003, during [[Hurricane Isabel]] and its high winds.<ref>{{cite news |title = Hurricane Isabel photo log |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/forcesofnature/isabel_photolog.html |work = Indepth:Forces of Nature |publisher = [[CBC News]] |date = September 18, 2003 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = US: Millions still without power a week after Hurricane Isabel |url = http://www.wsws.org/articles/2003/sep2003/isab-s25.shtml |last = Martin |first = Patrick |publisher = [[World Socialist Website]] |date = September 25, 2003 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref> On August 27, 2011, the bridge was closed to all traffic due to the impact of [[Hurricane Irene]]. Then-Governor [[Martin O'Malley]] ordered the bridge closed when sustained winds exceeded {{convert|55|mph|km/h}}. On October 29, 2012, the bridge was closed due to the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]].<ref>{{cite web |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge Now Closed |url = http://www.wboc.com/story/19944902/chesapeake-bay-bridge-now-clo |publisher = WBOC TV |access-date = October 29, 2012 }}</ref> On March 6, 2013, during the [[March 2013 nor'easter]], high winds again caused the bridge to be closed.<ref>{{cite web |title = High winds force closure of Chesapeake Bay Bridge |url = http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20130306/NEWS/130306014/High-winds-force-closure-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge |publisher = Delaware Online |date = March 6, 2013 |access-date = March 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2008, a tractor trailer involved in a head-on collision near the west end fell from the bridge; the driver died in the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081100422.html?nav=hcmodule |title = Traffic Continues to Stall on Bay Bridge |last1 = St. George |first1 = Donna |last2 = Birnbaum |first2 = Michael |newspaper = The Washington Post |date = August 11, 2008 |access-date = August 11, 2008 |postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> The incident has highlighted concern that the bridge may not be structurally safe, but the [[Maryland Transportation Authority]] (MDTA) has discounted any structural or engineering problems with it.<ref name=\"structsafe-wjz\">{{cite news |url = http://wjz.com/local/bay.bridge.crash.2.792465.html |title = Eastbound Right Lane Reopens On Bay Bridge |last = May |first = Adam |date = August 11, 2008 |work = WJZ |access-date = August 12, 2008 }}</ref><!-- most of the content of the WJZ cite is derived from the AP cite without mentioning this fact --> Inspections of the wall in the weeks following the accident revealed that there was deterioration in the form of corrosion of the steel reinforcements inside barriers; this prompted immediate repairs to the wall.<ref>{{cite news |first = Alex |last = Dominguez |title = Bay Bridge walls had corrosion, tests show |url = http://fredericksburg.com//News/FLS/2008/082008/08272008/405943 |newspaper = The Free Lance-Star |date = August 27, 2008 |access-date = August 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508063111/http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2008/082008/08272008/405943 |archivedate = May 8, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Specifications and operations==\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge from Sandy Point State Park.jpg|thumb|Chesapeake Bay Bridge from Sandy Point State Park]]\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge MD1.jpg|thumb|right|View of both spans from the [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]] side, in which the original 1952 span appears in front of the newer 1973 span.]]\nWith shore-to-shore lengths of {{convert|4.33|and|4.35|mi|km}},<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> the two spans of the bridge form the longest fixed water crossing in Maryland and ranked 102nd among the world's [[List of bridges by length|longest over-water structures]]. The bridge's western terminus is in [[Sandy Point State Park]], located northeast of [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] in [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel County]], and its eastern terminus is in [[Stevensville, Maryland|Stevensville]] on [[Kent Island, Maryland|Kent Island]] in [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]].[[File:20030519BayBridge.jpg|thumb|left|A May 2003 sunset behind the Bay Bridge]]\n\n===Structural details===\nWith the exception of the number of lanes on each (two on the original span and three on the newer span) and differences owing to the design standards for the periods in which they were built, the spans are structurally similar. Both were designed by [[J. E. Greiner Company]],<ref>{{Cite book |url = http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/maintainRoadsBridges/bridges/oppe/bridgebook/bridge_book.asp |last1 = Legler |first1 = Dixie |last2 = Highsmith |first2 = Carol |year = 2002 |title = Historic Bridges of Maryland |pages = 46 |location = Crownsville, Md. |publisher = Maryland Historic Trust |isbn = 1-878399-80-2 |postscript   =|url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090510070141/http://www.sha.state.md.us/KeepingCurrent/maintainRoadsBridges/bridges/oppe/bridgebook/bridge_book.asp |archivedate = 2009-05-10 |df = }}</ref> which later became a part of [[AECOM]] through the company's acquisition of [[URS Corporation]]. Each span features:\n*Two main spans over the bay's two shipping channels:\n**A {{convert|3200|ft|m|0|adj=on}} [[Suspension bridge|suspension]] span over the western channel with a maximum clearance of {{convert|186|ft|m|1}}\u2014high enough to accommodate ocean-going vessels and [[tall ship]]s\n**A through-truss [[Cantilever bridge|cantilever]] span over the eastern channel with a maximum clearance of {{convert|58|ft|m}}\n*Deck truss and steel girder spans flanking the main spans\n*Concrete beam spans on the portions closest to the shores\n*A curve near the western terminus, which is required so that the main spans cross the bay's shipping channels at 90 degrees per [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] requirements<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid= |title = William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial Bridge: Fun Facts [Family Fun] |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = October 9, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928035027/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid= |archive-date = September 28, 2007 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Traffic control===\n[[File:Chesapeake bay bridge sunset.jpg|200px|thumb|left|The westbound span at sunset. The leftmost lane is closed to westbound traffic.]]\nTraffic patterns on the bridge's five lanes can be adjusted via its [[reversible lane|lane control]] system, which consists of overhead lane control signals on both spans and approaches. Typically, the two lanes on the south-most span are configured for vehicles traveling east on eastbound US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301, while the three lanes on the north-most span are configured for vehicles traveling west on westbound US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301; the spans are therefore referred to as the \"eastbound span\" and \"westbound span\", respectively. However, this pattern is adjusted during incidents or peak travel times: for instance, on the outset of weekends when there is a high volume of beach-bound traffic, one lane on the westbound span is configured for eastbound traffic.\n\nIn 2006, pink markers were placed along the eastbound span to mark out the suggested following distance, similar to systems used in [[Minnesota]] and [[Pennsylvania]]. The markers are a part of the MDTA's \"Pace Your Space\" campaign to prevent [[car accident|vehicle collisions]] and [[traffic congestion]] due to [[tailgating]] on the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridgeproject.com/safetytips.html |title = SAFETY TIPS for traveling the Bay Bridge |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227222434/http://www.baybridgeproject.com/safetytips.html |archivedate = December 27, 2007 |df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.stateline.org/live/details/story?contentId=125133 |title = State DOTs hope drivers see dots |last = Gramlich |first = John |publisher = Stateline.Org |date = July 7, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, changes were made to increase safety on the westbound span during two-way operations: signs, pavement markings, and rumble strips were modified, and a buffer zone between the left and center lanes was created. As a result, motorists can no longer switch between the left and center lanes, whether or not two-way operations are in effect.<ref>{{cite web |title = Plans made to enhance two-way traffic operations on Chesapeake Bay Bridge |url = http://www.wbaltv.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel-county/Plans-made-to-enhance-two-way-traffic-operations-on-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge/-/10137088/19805934/-/stpg8kz/-/index.html |publisher = WBAL TV |access-date = June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130620022345/http://www.wbaltv.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel-county/Plans-made-to-enhance-two-way-traffic-operations-on-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge/-/10137088/19805934/-/stpg8kz/-/index.html |archivedate = June 20, 2013 |df   =}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last = Thomson |first = Candy |title = Bay Bridge getting rumble strips, safety buffer zone |url = http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/breaking/bs-md-bay-bridge-safety-20130418,0,7871261.story |newspaper = Baltimore Sun |access-date = June 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Tolls and fees===\n\nOperated by the MDTA, the bridge has a one-way toll (eastbound) of $4.00 for two-axle vehicles; vehicles with a Maryland [[E-ZPass]] pay $2.50.<ref>{{cite web |title = Toll Rates |url = http://www.baybridge.maryland.gov/toll-rates |website = baybridge.maryland.gov |access-date = June 11, 2017 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref> Previously the bridge had a one-way (eastbound) toll of $6.00 for two-axle vehicles (raised from $4 on July 1, 2013); vehicles with E-ZPass that were enrolled in the Bay Bridge Commuter Plan paid $2.10 (raised from $1 on July 1, 2013).<ref>{{cite web |title = Toll Rates for the William Preston Lane Jr. Memorial (Bay) Bridge (US 50/301) |url = http://www.mdta.maryland.gov/TollRates/baybridge_rates.html |access-date = July 10, 2014 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref>\n\nTolls were collected in both directions until April 1989, when tolls were doubled and only collected in the Eastbound direction.<ref>{{cite news |title=WESTBOUND BAY BRIDGE TOLL ENDING |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1989/02/01/westbound-bay-bridge-toll-ending/82181e67-d90e-48f0-b3d3-f9e111731782 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=Feb 1, 1989}}</ref>\n\nThe MDTA contracts with private companies to provide transportation across the bridge for nervous drivers ([[gephyrophobia]]cs) and cyclists; fees are $25 and $30 for drivers and cyclists, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24&Itemid= |title = Safe Travel Tips |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = November 30, 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091006060747/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24&Itemid= |archive-date = October 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Bay Bridge Walk and Run==\nWhile there are no pedestrian facilities on the bridge, the Bay Bridge Walk and Governor's Bay Bridge Run used to afford an opportunity to cross the bridge on foot, usually on the first Sunday in May.<ref name=release>{{cite press release |title = Governor O'Malley Announces Plans to Host 2007 Bay Bridge Walk |publisher = Maryland Department of Transportation |date = February 23, 2007 |url = http://www.e-mdot.com/News/2007/February%202007/Bay%20Bridge%20walk.htm |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121154709/http://www.e-mdot.com/News/2007/February%202007/Bay%20Bridge%20walk.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date = November 21, 2008 |access-date = September 1, 2008 |quote = The first Sunday in May means Bay Bridge Walk }}</ref> The events took place on the eastbound span, which was closed to vehicles while two-way traffic shared the westbound span. Participants started on the east end of the bridge (on Kent Island) and proceeded west to the finish near the toll plaza. [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority|WMATA]] and [[Maryland Transit Administration|MTA]] transit buses transported participants between outlying parking areas and the start and finish points.\n\nThe run, a [[10,000 metres|10K]] race across the bridge, is held early in the morning before the walk. It is conducted by the Annapolis Striders, a local running organization, and controlled by the MDTA and [[Maryland Department of Natural Resources]]. Proceeds went to the Chesapeake Bay Trust in support of the bay.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://annapolisstriders.org/gbbrInfo2007.htm |title = The 22nd Governor\u2019s Bay Bridge Run |access-date = November 16, 2007 |publisher = Annapolis Striders |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055606/http://annapolisstriders.org/gbbrInfo2007.htm |archivedate = October 27, 2007 |df = }}</ref>\n\nThe walk was first held in 1975,<ref name=\"Roads to the Future-walk\">{{cite web |url = http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesa_Bay_Bridge_Walk.html |title = Chesapeake Bay Bridge Walk |last = Kozel |first = Scott |access-date = November 16, 2007 |work = Roads to the Future }}</ref> after a [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scout]] leader in [[Towson, Maryland|Towson]] asked then-Governor [[Marvin Mandel]] if his troop could walk across the bridge while it was closed for maintenance.<ref name=release /> The annual walk was canceled for the first time in 1980 due to poor weather conditions, and later saw frequent cancellations throughout the 2000s. During this period the walk was canceled in:\n*2002 and 2007 due to poor weather conditions.<ref name=\"WJZ-2007 walk cancelled\">{{cite news |title = High Winds Cancel Bay Bridge Walk |last = Schuyler |first = Jim |url = http://wjz.com/topstories/local_story_126105130.html |publisher = [[WJZ-TV]] |date = May 6, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227223020/http://wjz.com/topstories/local_story_126105130.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archive-date = December 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post: race canceled\">{{cite news |title = Race Canceled for 4th Time in Six Years |last = Yanovits |first = Dave |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/06/AR2007050601014.html |newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] |date = May 7, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n*2003 and 2005 due to security concerns.<ref name=\"Washington Post: race canceled\" />\n*2008, 2009, and 2010 due to construction activity in the area on the west side of the bridge where participants would otherwise be staged.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.wtop.com/?nid=715&sid=1305650 |title = Bay Bridge Walk Canceled for 2008, 2009 |date = December 6, 2007 |publisher = WTOP News |access-date = February 6, 2008 }}</ref> Fiscal concerns were also cited as a contributing factor to the 2010 cancellation.<ref>{{Cite journal |url = http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=598&sid=1903428 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130105104839/http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=598&sid=1903428 |url-status=dead |archive-date = January 5, 2013 |publisher = WTOP |last = Basch |first = Michelle |title = Bay Bridge Walk cancelled for 4th year in a row |accessdate = March 14, 2010 |postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref>\n*2011 due to fiscal concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid= |title = Bay Bridge |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |author = Eric Willison |date = April 14, 2015 |work = baybridge.com |access-date = March 31, 2011 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110303041037/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid= |archive-date = March 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n*2012 for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |title = No Bridge Walk Scheduled in 2012 |url = http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20120904071539/http://www.baybridge.com/cms/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17 |url-status=dead |archive-date = 2012-09-04 |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}</ref>\n\nFollowing its cancellation in 2005, the MDTA considered decreasing the annual frequency of the event, citing traffic, fiscal, manpower, and security concerns. The most recent event (held in 2006) cost over $350,000, and the cost estimate for 2012 was almost $400,000. In late 2011, a non-profit group, the [[Greater Washington Sports Alliance]] (GWSA), approached the MDTA Capital Committee to propose sponsoring the event, along with a concert at Sandy Point State Park, at no cost to the MDTA. While the Capital Committee unanimously recommended that the MDTA Board approve the proposal contingent upon an agreement between the GWSA and the MDTA, the 2012 event was ultimately cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title = Monthly Capital Meeting Minutes for October 13, 2011 |url = http://www.mdta.maryland.gov/MeetingSchedules/Meeting_Minutes/CapComm_Minutes_10-13-2011.pdf |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAfter increasingly consistent cancellations of the walking event, the MDTA, along with [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]], contracted with an outside company to have a professional 10K race across the bridge, which has been labeled the \"Across the Bay 10K\". The inaugural event occurred November 9, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://delmarvatowncrier.com/archives/just-announced-10k-race-across-the-chesapeake-bay-bridge/ |title = Just Announced: 10K Race Across the Chesapeake Bay Bridge |date = March 27, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |newspaper = Delmarva Town Crier }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.myeasternshoremd.com/news/queen_annes_county/article_5336e54c-9bba-11e2-a5f5-0019bb2963f4.html |title = Officials say OK to bridge 10K |date = April 2, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |first = Jordan |last = Shatz }}</ref> The Race Director is [[Dave McGillivray]],<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.runningusa.org/10K-across-the-bay-dmse-mcgillivray?returnTo=2013 |title = McGillivray to Direct 10K Across the Bay |newspaper = Running USA |date = July 17, 2013 |access-date = July 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140727220639/http://www.runningusa.org/10K-across-the-bay-dmse-mcgillivray?returnTo=2013 |archivedate = July 27, 2014 |df   =}}</ref> who has served in that capacity for the BAA Boston Marathon since 1988. The Across the Bay 10K will have several charity beneficiaries, including bay research and restoration as well as breast cancer research and several others.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwfitness/article/Registration-Opens-for-Across-the-Bay-10K-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge-Run-Today-20131108 |title = Registration Opens for 'Across the Bay 10K' Chesapeake Bay Bridge Run Today |date = November 9, 2013 |access-date = December 5, 2013 |publisher = Wisdom Digital Media |quote = Runners are encouraged to fundraise for charity and last week two charities were selected to benefit from the race |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140729171707/http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwfitness/article/Registration-Opens-for-Across-the-Bay-10K-Chesapeake-Bay-Bridge-Run-Today-20131108 |archive-date = 2014-07-29 |url-status=dead |df   =}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Race Charity Partners |url = http://bridgerace.com/official-partners.php |access-date = December 5, 2013 |publisher = CBBR |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131115064907/http://www.bridgerace.com/official-partners.php |archivedate = November 15, 2013 |df = }}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Ocean City MD beach looking north from pier.jpeg|thumb|left|In the years since the bridge's completion, Ocean City (pictured) has experienced significant growth.]]\nSince its construction, the bridge has made significant impacts on both sides of the bay; among them has been the growth of [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]] communities. When the bridge opened in 1952, and again when the second span was added in 1973, the Eastern Shore was given easier access to [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], causing areas in southern [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland|Queen Anne's County]] to develop as [[commuter town|bedroom communities]]. This extension of the Baltimore\u2013Washington suburbs has led Queen Anne's County to be listed as part of the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Metropolitan Area]]. The bridge has also given easier access to [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]] from the [[Western Shore]], which has caused Ocean City to grow from a small town to one that is said to become the second largest city in Maryland during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?pagename=article&node=&contentId=A18858-2002Jul29&notFound=true |title = Spanning Half a Century |last = Johnson |first = Darragh |author2 = Hernandez, Nelson |newspaper = The Washington Post |date = July 30, 2002 |access-date = October 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, the impending completion of the bridge gave rise to an extension of [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland|US&nbsp;50]] to Ocean City.<ref>{{cite web |title = End of U.S. highway 50 |url = http://www.geocities.com/usend5059/End050/end050.htm |date = August 10, 2007 |access-date = November 16, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090729182235/http://geocities.com/usend5059/End050/end050.htm |archive-date = July 29, 2009 }}</ref> The route was extended along the corridor of [[Maryland Route 404]] (MD&nbsp;404) and a large portion of [[U.S. Route 213|US&nbsp;213]], cutting both of those routes back. During the 1950s, US&nbsp;50 on the Western Shore was rerouted onto the long-proposed [[U.S. Route 50 in Maryland#John Hanson Highway|Annapolis\u2013Washington Expressway]] (now known as the John Hanson Highway), which was built at the time in order to provide better access to the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.dcroads.net/roads/I-595_MD/ |title = John Hanson Highway |last = Anderson |first = Steve |publisher = dcroads.net |access-date = February 6, 2008 }}</ref> As the Eastern Shore, particularly Ocean City, grew, further upgrades and realignments of US&nbsp;50 took place. This work included the aforementioned 1973 completion of the second Bay Bridge span, the extension of the US&nbsp;50 freeway eastward to the US&nbsp;50/US&nbsp;301 split in [[Queenstown, Maryland|Queenstown]], and the construction of a freeway bypass around the north side of Salisbury in 2002. Additionally, the road has been upgraded and realigned over the years from its original two-lane configuration to a four-lane [[divided highway]], with the last such section being in [[Vienna, Maryland|Vienna]], bypassed in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.delmarvahighways.com/old50-vienna.htm |title = Abandoned US 50 / US 213, Vienna, MD |last = Dukes |first = Corey |publisher = Delmarva Highways |date = August 1, 2007 |accessdate = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071020050833/http://www.delmarvahighways.com/old50-vienna.htm |archivedate = October 20, 2007 |df   =}}</ref> As of 2008, there are plans for further upgrades to US&nbsp;50, including extending its freeway portion in Queen Anne's County to MD&nbsp;404 outside of [[Wye Mills, Maryland|Wye Mills]] and replacing the aging [[Harry W. Kelly Memorial Bridge]] into Ocean City.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.delmarvahighways.com/us50.htm |title = Ocean Gateway \u2013 Ocean City, MD to MD 90 Interchange |last = Dukes |first = Corey |publisher = Delmarva Highways |date = January 19, 2004 |access-date = October 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927045828/http://www.delmarvahighways.com/us50.htm |archive-date = September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is often the site of [[Suicide bridge|suicides]] by jumpers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecildaily.com/local_news/police-confirm-the-identity-of-bridge-jumper/article_7e334ff8-f529-11e0-bafd-001cc4c03286.html|title=Police confirm the identity of bridge jumper|first=Carl Hamilton|last=cahamilton@ceciwhig.com|website=Cecil Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecildaily.com/news/state_news/one-man-dies-another-injured-in-jumps-from-bay-bridge/article_bdaac432-0fbd-11e1-8f66-001cc4c03286.html|title=One man dies, another injured in jumps from Bay Bridge|website=Cecil Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbc26.com/news/national/maryland-first-responder-saves-man-from-suicide-on-chesapeake-bay-bridge|title=First responder saves man from suicide on bridge|date=12 April 2018|website=WGBA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/nov/30/man-jumps-chesapeake-bay-bridge/|title=Man jumps off Chesapeake Bay Bridge in Maryland|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|website=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/3-plunge-from-bay-bridge-2-killed|title=3 plunge from Bay Bridge; 2 killed|date=18 April 2011|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n==Future expansion==\n[[File:Chesapeake Bay Bridge Aerial.jpg|thumb|Chesapeake Bay Bridge]]\n\n{{main|2005 Chesapeake Bay crossing study}}\nIn December 2004, a study concluded that traffic across the bridge was expected to increase by 40% by 2025. The following year, a task force formed by Governor [[Robert Ehrlich|Bob Ehrlich]] met to again explore the possibility of establishing a new Chesapeake Bay crossing.<ref name=\"second bridge\">{{cite news |last = Berman |first = Dori |url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4183/is_20050627/ai_n14693744 |title = Task force says second Chesapeake Bay bridge is best option |publisher = The Baltimore Daily Record |date = June 27, 2005 |access-date = February 5, 2008 }}</ref> The task force concluded that a bridge would be the best option for an additional crossing, and four geographic locations for such a bridge were explored: Baltimore County to Kent County, Anne Arundel County to Queen Anne's County (the existing location), Anne Arundel or Calvert County to Talbot County, and Calvert County to Dorchester County.<ref name=\"task force pdf\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/BayCrossing/BriefingBook/Taskforce_Briefing_Book_2-001.pdf |title = Meeting #2: Bridge, Traffic, and Highway Issues |publisher = Maryland Transportation Authority |access-date = February 5, 2008 |format = pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070124043621/http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/BayCrossing/BriefingBook/Taskforce_Briefing_Book_2-001.pdf |archive-date = January 24, 2007 }}</ref> In late 2006, the task force released a report on the study but did not make a final recommendation; members of the task force requested additional time to continue the study.<ref name=\"WTOP-report released\">{{cite news |last = Wyatt |first = Kristen |url = http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=25&sid=896776 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130105084049/http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=25&sid=896776 |url-status=dead |archive-date = January 5, 2013 |title = Bay Bridge Report Released without Recommendation |publisher = WTOP news |date = August 29, 2006 |access-date = February 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|Chesaspeake Bay Bridge Panorama 60465636.jpg|900px|Panoramic view of the bridge, looking south, in which the two main spans (suspension at center and through truss at left) are visible. The towers with the \"X\"-shaped latticework are on the eastbound (1952) suspension span, while those with the horizontal crossmembers are on the westbound (1973) suspension span. Notice the difference in the locations of the anchoring points of the main cables: at water level for the eastbound span and at deck level atop large concrete piers for the westbound span.}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Maryland}}\n*[[Kent Narrows Bridge]]\n*[[List of bridges by length]]\n*[[Severn River Bridge]]\n*[[St. Margaret's, Maryland]]\n*[[Cape St. Claire, Maryland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chesapeake Bay Bridge}}\n*{{osmrelation|1736026}}\n*[http://www.baybridge.com Chesapeake Bay Bridge official website]\n*[http://www.mdta.state.md.us/mdta/servlet/dispatchServlet?url=/TollFacilities/BayBridge.jsp Bay Bridge Page at MdTA website]\n*[http://www.roadstothefuture.com/Chesapeake_Bay_Bridge.html Roads to the Future website]\n*[http://www.dcroads.net/crossings/bay-bridge/ Page at dcroads.net]\n*{{Structurae|id=20000561|title=Chesapeake Bay Bridge}}\n*[http://www.chart.state.md.us/video/videolow.asp?feed=24 Live Video Rt 50 Kent Island]\n*[http://www.chart.state.md.us/video/videolow.asp?feed=2 Live Video Rt 50 Sandy Point]\n*[https://archive.org/details/probableeconomic62mary A 1950 comprehensive study of the economic effects of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge (pdf)]\n\n{{MdTA facilities}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure = Bridges\n|place = [[Chesapeake Bay]]\n|bridge = Chesapeake Bay Bridge\n|bridge signs = [[File:US 50.svg|20px]] [[File:US 301.svg|25px]]\n|upstream = [[P.W. & B. Railroad Bridge]] (ruins) <br /> ([[Susquehanna River]]) <br />\n[[Francis Scott Key Bridge (Baltimore)|Francis Scott Key Bridge]] <br /> ([[Patapsco River]]) <br>\n[[File:I-695.svg|25px]] <br>\n[[Chesapeake City Bridge]] <br> ([[Chesapeake and Delaware Canal]]) <br /> [[File:MD Route 213.svg|25px]]\n|downstream = [[Chesapeake Bay Bridge\u2013Tunnel]]\n|downstream signs = [[File:US 13.svg|20px]]\n}}\n\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1952]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1973]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Queen Anne's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the United States Numbered Highways]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chesapeake Bay]]\n[[Category:Concrete bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Girder bridges in the United States]]\n